)\n*[[Hokkaido Nippon Ham Fighters|Nippon Ham Fighters<br />Hokkaido Nippon Ham Fighters]] ({{Baseball year|2003}}\u2013{{Baseball year|2010}})\n*[[Orix Buffaloes]] ({{baseball year|2011}})\n*[[San Rafael Pacifics]] ({{baseball year|2012}})\n*[[Gary SouthShore RailCats]] ({{baseball year|2012}})\n*[[Rio Grande Valley WhiteWings]] ({{baseball year|2012}})\n*[[Edinburg Roadrunners]] ({{baseball year|2013}})\n*[[Lancaster Barnstormers]] ({{baseball year|2014}})\n'''As coach'''\n*[[Yokohama DeNA BayStars]] ({{Baseball year|2015}} \u2013 present)\n| highlights    = \n| update        = 28 August 2013\n}}\n\n'''Tomochika Tsuboi''' ({{lang-ja|'''\u576a\u4e95 \u667a\u54c9'''}}, born February 19, 1974 in [[K\u014dt\u014d, Tokyo]], Japan) is a Japanese [[baseball]] [[outfielder]]. He previously played in the [[Nippon Professional Baseball|NPB]] for 13 seasons, starting in 1998. His professional career started with the [[Hanshin Tigers]], but he was traded to the [[Nippon-Ham Fighters]] for [[Toshihiro Noguchi]] after the 2002 season. His stint with Nippon Ham was his longest with the same team, lasting through 2010. He then played briefly for the [[Orix Buffaloes]], his final season in Japanese pro ball. He declined a coaching position with the Fighters and since 2012 has played in various American [[independent league baseball|independent leagues]].\n\n==Biography==\n\n{{Empty section|date=July 2010}}\n\n==NPB statistics==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|- bgcolor=\"#CCCCCC\"\n! SEASON !! TEAM !! G   !! AB  !!  R  !!  H  !! 2B !! 3B !! HR !! RBI !! BB !! SO !! SB !! CS !! AVG  \n|-\n| 1998 || [[Hanshin Tigers|HT]] || 123 || 413 || 63 || 135 || 26 || 2 || 2 || 21 || 38 || 80 || 7 || 5 || .327 \n|-\n| 1999 || [[Hanshin Tigers|HT]] ||134||530||75||161||30||1||5|| 43 || 50 || 90 || 6 || 10 || .304 \n|-\n| 2000 || [[Hanshin Tigers|HT]]  ||128||489||49||133||14||4||4||32 || 50 || 83 || 6 || 6 || .272 \n|-\n| 2001 || [[Hanshin Tigers|HT]] ||43||128||12||28||7||2||2||11 || 11 || 30 || 1|| 