{"title_page": "John Young (astronaut)", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = John Watts Young\n| image         = Astronaut John W. Young.jpg\n| caption       =\n| nationality   = American\n| birth_name    = John Watts Young\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1930|09|24}}\n| birth_place   = [[San Francisco, California]], U.S.\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|2018|01|05|1930|09|24}}\n| death_place   = [[Seabrook, Texas]] U.S.\n| occupation    = [[United States Naval Aviator|Naval Aviator]], [[test pilot]]\n| alma_mater    = [[Georgia Institute of Technology]], B.S. 1952\n| module        = {{Infobox astronaut|child =yes\n| type          = [[NASA]] astronaut\n| rank          = {{Dodseal|USNO6|25}} [[Captain (United States O-6)|Captain]], [[United States Navy|USN]]\n| selection     = [[List of astronauts by year of selection#1962|1962 NASA Group 2]]\n| time          = 34d 19h 39m\n| eva1          = 3\n| eva2          = 20h 14m 14s\n| mission       = [[Gemini 3]], [[Gemini 10]], [[Apollo 10]], [[Apollo 16]], [[STS-1]], [[STS-9]]\n| insignia      = [[File:Gemini3.png|45px]] [[File:Gemini 10 Insignia.svg|54px]] [[File:Apollo-10-LOGO.png|45px]] [[File:Apollo-16-LOGO.png|45px]] [[File:Sts-1-patch.png|45px]] [[File:Sts-9-patch.png|45px]]\n| Date of ret   = December 31, 2004\n| awards        = [[File:Dfc-usa.jpg|20px|link=Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)]] {{CS Medal of Honor}} [[File:NASA Distinguished Service Medal.jpg|20px|link=NASA Distinguished Service Medal]]\n}}}}\n\n'''John Watts Young''' (September 24, 1930&nbsp;\u2013 January 5, 2018) was an American [[astronaut]], [[United States Navy|naval officer]] and [[United States Naval Aviator|aviator]], [[test pilot]], and [[aerospace engineering|aeronautical engineer]]. He became the [[List of Apollo astronauts#People who have walked on the Moon|ninth person to walk on the Moon]] as Commander of the [[Apollo 16]] mission in 1972. Young enjoyed the longest career of any astronaut, becoming the first person to fly six space missions over the course of 42 years of active [[NASA]] service.<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/htmlbios/young.html |title=Biographical Data: John W. Young (Captain, USN Ret.) |publisher=NASA |date=August 2010 |access-date=May 14, 2013}}</ref> He is the only person to have piloted and commanded four different classes of spacecraft: [[Project Gemini|Gemini]], the [[Apollo Command and Service Module]], the [[Apollo Lunar Module]], and the [[Space Shuttle]].<ref name=\"sentinel20160924\">{{cite news |last1=Speck |first1=Emilee |title=Moon-walking astronaut John Young turned 86 on Saturday |url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/space/go-for-launch/os-nasa-astronaut-john-young-turns-86-20160923-story.html |access-date=August 16, 2017 |work=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |date=September 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1965 Young flew on the [[Gemini 3|first crewed Gemini mission]], and then commanded the 1966 [[Gemini 10]] mission. In 1969 during [[Apollo 10]], he became the first person to fly solo around the Moon.<ref name=\"nasa200412007\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/vision/space/features/young_retires.html |title=From Gemini to Shuttle: John Young Retires |publisher=NASA |date=December 7, 2004 |access-date=January 7, 2018}}</ref> He then walked on the Moon and drove the [[Lunar Roving Vehicle]] on the Moon's surface during [[Apollo 16]], and is one of only three people to have [[List of Apollo astronauts|flown to the Moon]] twice.<ref name=\"npr20180106\">{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2017/01/16/505928876/gene-cernan-last-man-to-walk-on-the-moon-dies-at-82 |title=Gene Cernan, Last Man To Walk On The Moon, Dies At 82 |publisher=NPR |last1=Lewis |first1=Russell |date=January 6, 2018 |access-date=January 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nYoung also commanded two flights of [[Space Shuttle Columbia|Space Shuttle ''Columbia'']]: [[STS-1]] in 1981, the [[Space Shuttle]] program's first launch, and [[STS-9]] in 1983. Young served as [[Chief of the Astronaut Office]] from 1974 to 1987, and retired from NASA in 2004.\n\n==Early years and education==\nYoung was born in [[San Francisco, California]], on September 24, 1930,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28981374/the_orlando_sentinel/ |title=Astronauts Could Have a Party |newspaper=The Orlando Sentinel |location=Orlando, Florida |date=February 3, 1963 |page=15 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> to parents William Hugh Young, a civil engineer,<ref name=\"nyt20180106\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/06/obituaries/john-young-dead.html |title=John Young, Who Led First Space Shuttle Mission, Dies at 87 |work=[[The New York Times]] |first=Richard |last=Goldstein |date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> and Wanda Howland Young.<ref name=\"navy-history-young\">{{cite web |url=http://www.history.navy.mil/research/histories/biographies-list/bios-y/Young-John/Young-John-Text.html |title=John Watts Young |publisher=Navy Office of Information, Biographies Branch |date=April 10, 1972}}</ref> At 18 months old, due to the [[Great Depression]], he moved with his family to [[Cartersville, Georgia|Cartersville]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]],<ref name=\"fortune20180106\">{{cite news |url=http://amp.timeinc.net/fortune/2018/01/06/astronaut-john-young-dead |title=Astronaut John Young, One of Only 12 to Walk on Moon, Dies at 87 |work=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] |agency=[[Bloomberg News]] |date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> then to [[Orlando, Florida]], where he attended grade school and later [[Orange County Public Schools#High schools|Orlando High School]] until graduating in 1948.<ref name=\"sjg19650324\">{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=HhpdAAAAIBAJ&pg=1598%2C4411712 |title=John Young, as Early as 1946, Displayed Interest in Rockets |work=[[St. Joseph Gazette]] |agency=Associated Press |volume=120 |issue=238 |page=6A |date=March 24, 1965 |access-date=May 14, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"jwy-edu\">{{cite web |url=http://www.johnwyoung.org/bio/education.htm |title=Biography: Education |work=JohnWYoung.org |access-date=May 14, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061128151906/http://www.johnwyoung.org/bio/education.htm |archive-date=November 28, 2006 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Young was a [[Scouts BSA (Boy Scouts of America)|Boy Scout]] and earned the rank of [[Second Class (Boy Scouts of America)|Second Class]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scouting.org/About/FactSheets/scouting_space.aspx |title=Scouting and Space Exploration |website=Scouting.org |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303213130/http://www.scouting.org/about/factsheets/scouting_space.aspx |archivedate=March 3, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nYoung earned a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree with highest honors in [[Aerospace engineering|Aeronautical Engineering]] from the [[Georgia Institute of Technology]] in 1952; while attending, he became a member of the national military honor society [[Scabbard and Blade]] and [[Sigma Chi]] fraternity.<ref name=\"fw4465\">{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1774&dat=19650404&id=AZscAAAAIBAJ&pg=5001,1212947 |title=Virgil Grissom and John Young: Our Trail-Blazing \"Twin\" Astronauts |work=[[Sarasota Herald-Tribune]] |series=Family Weekly |first=John W. |last=Wasik |page=4 |date=April 4, 1965 |access-date=January 28, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"blueprint1952\">{{cite book |url=http://hdl.handle.net/1853/25833 |title=Blue Print |publisher=[[Georgia Institute of Technology]] |editor-first=Blount |editor-last=Boswell |volume=45 |page=108 |date=1952}}</ref>\n\n==Navy service==\n{{quote box|align=right|width=28%|quote=I got a telegram from the [[Chief of Naval Operations]] asking me not to do this anymore.|salign=right|source=\u2014Young, describing an air-to-air missile test in which he and another pilot approached each other at Mach 3 - risking destruction of both aircraft.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.johnwyoung.org/bio/navycareer.htm |title=Astronaut John W. Young - Navy Career |website=Johnwyoung.org}}</ref>}}\n\nAfter graduating from [[Georgia Institute of Technology|Georgia Tech]] in 1952, Young entered the [[United States Navy]] through the [[Naval Reserve Officers Training Corps|Navy ROTC]] and was commissioned on June 6, 1952, as an [[ensign (rank)|ensign]].<ref name=\"navy-history-young\" /> He served as fire control officer on the destroyer {{USS|Laws|DD-558|6}} until June 1953 and completed a tour in the [[Sea of Japan]] during the [[Korean War]]. Following this assignment, he was sent to flight training. In January 1954, he was designated a Navy helicopter pilot.<ref name=\"navy-history-young\" /> After receiving his [[United States Naval Aviator|aviator wings]] on December 20, 1954, he was assigned to Fighter Squadron 103 ([[VFA-103|VF-103]]) for four years, flying [[Grumman F9F Cougar]]s from {{USS|Coral Sea|CV-43|6}} and [[Vought F8U Crusader]]s from {{USS|Forrestal|CV-59|6}}.<ref name=\"nmmuseum\" />\n\nAfter training at the [[United States Naval Test Pilot School]] in 1959 with the Class 23, Young was assigned to the Naval Air Test Center at [[Naval Air Station Patuxent River]], Maryland, for three years. His test projects included evaluations of the [[Vought XF8U-3 Crusader III|XF8U-3 Crusader III]] and [[McDonnell Douglas F-4 Phantom II|F-4 Phantom II]] fighter weapons systems. In 1962, he set two world time-to-climb records while flying his Phantom II, attaining {{convert|3000|m|ft|0|sp=us}} from a standing start in 34.52 seconds and {{convert|25000|m|ft|0|sp=us}} from a standing start in 227.6 seconds.<ref name=\"navy-history-young\" /> He also served as maintenance officer of Fighter Squadron 143 ([[VFA-143|VF-143]]) from April to September 1962.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nFellow astronaut [[Charles Bolden]] described Young and [[Robert L. Gibson|Robert \"Hoot\" Gibson]] as the two best pilots he had met during his aviation career: \"Never met two people like them. Everyone else gets into an airplane; John and Hoot wear their airplane. They're just awesome\".<ref name=\"bolden20040106\">{{cite interview |title=Charles F. Bolden |date=January 6, 2004 |access-date=January 6, 2014 |last=Bolden |first=Charles F. |subjectlink=Charles Bolden |interviewer1=Johnson, Sandra |interviewer2=Wright, Rebecca |interviewer3=Ross-Nazzal, Jennifer |work=NASA Johnson Space Center Oral History Project |location=Houston, Texas |url=http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/history/oral_histories/BoldenCF/BoldenCF_1-6-04.htm}}</ref> Young retired from the Navy as a [[Captain (naval)|Captain]] in September 1976, after 25 years.<ref name=\"nmmuseum\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nmspacemuseum.org/halloffame/detail.php?id=70 |title=Commanded the first shuttle flight, the first person to enter space six times |publisher=New Mexico Museum of Space History |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==NASA career==\n===Project Gemini===\n{{Main|Gemini 3|Gemini 10}}\n[[File:Astronaut John Young gemini 3.jpg|left|thumb|Young, age 34, as pilot of Gemini 3]]\nJoining [[NASA]] in 1962, Young was the first of the [[NASA Astronaut Group 2|Astronaut Group 2]] to fly in space, replacing [[Thomas P. Stafford]] as pilot of [[Gemini 3]] when [[Alan Shepard]], the original command pilot, was grounded due to [[M\u00e9ni\u00e8re's disease]].{{sfn|Thompson|2004|p=366}} Making the first crewed flight of the Gemini spacecraft with [[Gus Grissom]] in 1965, Young scored another space first by smuggling a corned beef sandwich onto the spacecraft\u2014a feat for which he was reprimanded. Some members of the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]] were not pleased about the stunt, claiming that Young cost taxpayers millions of dollars by disrupting a scheduled test of space food during the flight.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://gizmodo.com/50-years-ago-nasa-astronauts-smuggled-a-corned-beef-sa-1693431694 |title=50 Years Ago, NASA Astronauts Smuggled a Corned Beef Sandwich Into Space |work=Gizmodo |last1=Zhang |first1=Sarah |date=March 24, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/history/mission_trans/GT03_TEC.PDF |title=Composite Air-to-ground and Onboard Voice Tape Transcription of the GT-3 Mission |publisher=National Astronautics and Space Administration |page=45 |date=April 1965 |access-date=May 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\nYoung then trained as backup pilot for [[Gemini 6A]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/multimedia/imagegallery/image_feature_1010.html |title=Gemini 6 Back-up Crew |publisher=NASA |date=March 23, 2008 |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> The assignment of [[Gemini 7]] backup command pilot [[Ed White (astronaut)|Ed White]] to Apollo, created an opening for Young as commander of [[Gemini 10]] in 1966.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MYasNyKQIxMC&pg=PA151&lpg=PA151 |title=Foothold in the Heavens: The Seventies |series=A History of Human Space Exploration |publisher=[[Springer Science+Business Media]] |last1=Evans |first1=Ben |page=151 |date=August 14, 2010 |isbn=978-1-4419-6341-3 |doi=10.1007/978-1-4419-6342-0}}</ref> The mission was the first to perform a rendezvous with two [[Agena target vehicle]]s; and his pilot, [[Michael Collins (astronaut)|Michael Collins]], performed two spacewalks.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.space.com/37527-gemini-10-photos.html |title=Gemini 10: NASA's Epic 1st Double Rendezvous Mission in Photos |work=Space.com |last1=Lunsford |first1=Christine |date=September 18, 2017 |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/nmc/spacecraft/display.action?id=1966-066A |title=Gemini 10 |publisher=NASA Space Science Data Coordinated Archive |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Apollo program===\n{{Main|Apollo 10|Apollo 16}}\n[[File:John W. Young on the Moon.jpg|right|thumb|Young jumps while saluting the [[Lunar Flag Assembly|American flag]] during Apollo 16]]\nIn 1966, Young was assigned to an Apollo crew as [[Apollo Command/Service Module|Command Module]] pilot, with Commander [[Thomas P. Stafford|Thomas Stafford]] and [[Apollo Lunar Module|Lunar Module]] pilot [[Eugene Cernan]]. This crew was assigned as backup to the second crewed Apollo mission, planned before the [[Apollo 1]] fire. After that fire, both crews{{clarify|date=March 2019}} were assigned to the first actual crewed mission, [[Apollo 7]], which flew in October 1968.<ref name=\"bio\" /> In May 1969, this crew flew to the Moon on [[Apollo 10]]. While Stafford and Cernan flew the Lunar Module in lunar orbit for the first time, Young flew the Command Module solo. Apollo 10 set the record for the highest speed attained by any crewed vehicle at {{convert|39897|km/h|mph}} during its return to Earth on May 26, 1969.<ref name=\"Guinness2012\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=biWfNzQiR8EC&pg=PA322 |title=Guinness World Records 2012 |publisher=[[Bantam Books]] |editor-first=Craig |editor-last=Glenday |page=322 |date=2012 |isbn=978-0-345-53437-8}}</ref><ref name=\"Lloyd2010\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uCgRY6llQpYC&pg=PA280 |title=QI: The Book of General Ignorance |publisher=[[Faber and Faber]] |first1=John |last1=Lloyd |first2=John |last2=Mitchinson |edition=The Noticeably Stouter |page=280 |date=2010 |isbn=978-0-571-27378-2}}</ref>\n\nYoung was backup commander of [[Apollo 13]], the troubled mission in which the Moon landing was aborted because of an explosion in the Service Module.<ref name=\"backup\">{{cite web |url=https://airandspace.si.edu/explore-and-learn/topics/apollo/apollo-program/landing-missions/apollo13-crew.cfm |title=Apollo 13 Crew |publisher=Smithsonian National Air and Space Museum |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBy rotation, Young became commander of [[Apollo 16]], and studied [[geology]] with his crew while preparing for the mission.<ref name=sudburytraining>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=s-9UAAAAIBAJ&pg=1178,849265&dq=apollo+16+training&hl=en |title=Astronauts training in Ont. |agency=[[The Canadian Press]] |newspaper=[[Leader-Post|The Leader-Post]] |location=Regina, Saskatchewan |last=Dickie |first=Allan |date=July 7, 1971 |accessdate=November 26, 2011}}</ref> Apollo 16's lunar landing was almost aborted when a malfunction was detected in the SPS engine control system in the Service Module. It was determined that the problem could be worked around, and the mission continued.<ref name=overview>{{cite web |title=Descartes Surprise |url=http://www.hq.nasa.gov/alsj/a16/a16.summary.html |publisher=Apollo Lunar Surface Journal |accessdate=November 26, 2011}}</ref> On the surface, Young took three moonwalks in the [[Descartes Highlands]] with [[Charles Duke]] on April 21, 22 and 23, 1972, making Young the ninth person to walk on the surface of the Moon, while [[Ken Mattingly]] flew the Command Module in lunar orbit.<ref name=\"bio\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/apollo/missions/apollo16.html |title=Apollo 16 |date=July 8, 2009 |publisher=NASA |access-date=January 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nYoung's final assignment in Apollo was as the backup commander for Cernan on [[Apollo 17]]. The backup crew was originally the [[Apollo 15]] crew, but [[Deke Slayton]] removed them from the assignment when he learned they had taken a small statue to the Moon, as well as stamps that they sold to a dealer.<ref name=15backup>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=kAsUAAAAIBAJ&pg=5667,8302&dq=apollo+17+backup+crew&hl=en |title=Apollo crew warned about commercialism |newspaper=The Free Lance-Star |date=August 1, 1972 |accessdate=August 26, 2011}}</ref><ref name=nasmcrew>{{cite web |url=http://www.nasm.si.edu/collections/imagery/apollo/as17/a17crew.htm |title=Apollo 17 Crew |work=The Apollo Program |publisher=[[National Air and Space Museum]] |location=Washington, D.C. |accessdate=August 26, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Space Shuttle program===\n{{Main|STS-1|STS-9}}\nIn January 1973 Young was made Chief of the Space Shuttle Branch of the Astronaut Office. In January 1974, he became Chief of the Astronaut Office after the retirement of [[Alan Shepard]].<ref name=\"asf\">{{cite web |url=https://astronautscholarship.org/Astronauts/john-w-young/ |title=John Young |publisher=Astronaut Scholarship Foundation |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nYoung flew two missions of the Space Shuttle, both aboard the {{OV|Columbia}}. He commanded the program's 1981 maiden orbital flight, [[STS-1]], and in 1983 commanded [[STS-9]], which carried the first [[Spacelab]] module.<ref name=\"asf\" /> In 1986 he was in line to make a record seventh space flight on [[Canceled Space Shuttle missions#Canceled due to the Challenger disaster|STS-61-J]] to deploy the [[Hubble Space Telescope]], but the [[Space Shuttle Challenger disaster|Space Shuttle ''Challenger'' disaster]] earlier that year had delayed NASA's schedule.<ref name=\"sts61\">{{cite web |url=http://www.astronautix.com/flights/sts61j.htm |title=STS-61-J |publisher=Encyclopedia Astronautica |date=November 17, 2007 |accessdate=March 31, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100108041720/http://astronautix.com/flights/sts61j.htm |archivedate=January 8, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nYoung was openly critical of NASA management following the ''Challenger'' disaster,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Technology/wireStory/nasa-legendary-astronaut-moonwalker-john-young-died-52180080 |title=NASA: Legendary astronaut, moonwalker John Young has died |last1=Dunn |first1=Marcia |publisher=ABC News |date=January 6, 2018 |access-date=January 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180106202306/http://abcnews.go.com/Technology/wireStory/nasa-legendary-astronaut-moonwalker-john-young-died-52180080 |archive-date=January 6, 2018 |url-status=dead}}</ref> and in April 1987 was made Special Assistant to JSC Director [[Aaron Cohen (Deputy NASA administrator)|Aaron Cohen]] for Engineering, Operations and Safety.<ref name=\"bio\" /> NASA denied that his criticism triggered the move, although Young and industry insiders believed that was the reason for the reassignment.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1987-04-16/news/mn-711_1_johnson-space-center-in-houston |title=The Nation |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=April 16, 1987 |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1987-07-30/news/mn-378_1_shuttle-flight |title=Top Astronaut Says NASA Forced Him From Job |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=July 30, 1987 |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> In February 1996, he was assigned as Associate Director (Technical) JSC.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nDuring his NASA career, Young logged more than 15,000 hours of training, mostly in simulators, to prepare for positions on eleven spaceflights in prime and backup crew positions.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\n===Retirement===\n[[File:John Young 2006.jpg|right|thumb|upright|Young at the 25th anniversary of STS-1 at [[Kennedy Space Center]]]]\nYoung worked for NASA for 42 years and announced his retirement on December 7, 2004. He retired on December 31, 2004, at the age of 74, but continued to attend the Monday Morning Meeting at the Astronaut Office at JSC for several years thereafter.<ref name=\"Fuglesang\">{{Cite book |title=Tretton dygn i rymden efter fjorton \u00e5r p\u00e5 jorden: dagbok fr\u00e5n rymden |trans-title=Thirteen days in space, after fourteen years on earth: a diary from space |language=Swedish |publisher=Albert Bonniers F\u00f6rlag |first=Christer |last=Fuglesang |date=2007 |isbn=978-91-85555-15-4 |oclc=185242561}}</ref> He logged more than 15,275 hours flying time in [[Powered aircraft#Propeller aircraft|props]], [[Jet aircraft|jets]], [[helicopter]]s, and [[Rocket-powered aircraft|rocket jets]]; more than 9,200 hours in [[Northrop T-38 Talon|T-38]]s; and 835 hours in [[spacecraft]] during six space flights.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nOn April 12, 2006, Young appeared at the 25th anniversary of the STS-1 launch at the [[Kennedy Space Center Visitor Complex]], along with pilot [[Robert Crippen]]. The two spoke of their experiences during the flight.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://mediaarchive.ksc.nasa.gov/detail.cfm?mediaid=28394 |title=To honor the 25th anniversary ... |publisher=NASA |first=Jeanne |last=Ryba |date=April 7, 2006 |access-date=October 6, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100531211821/http://mediaarchive.ksc.nasa.gov/detail.cfm?mediaid=28394 |archivedate=May 31, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Young published an autobiography, ''Forever Young''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.upf.com/book.asp?id=YOUNG001 |title=Forever Young: A Life of Adventure in Air and Space |work=University Press of Florida |access-date=May 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nYoung married Barbara White of [[Savannah, Georgia]], and they had two children, Sandra and John.<ref name=\"fw4465\" /> They were divorced in 1972 after 16 years of marriage.<ref name=\"telegraph19810411\">{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=gKgrAAAAIBAJ&pg=5388%2C2658262 |title=Young: America's old man of space |work=[[Nashua Telegraph]] |agency=Associated Press |volume=113 |issue=36 |page=23 |date=April 11, 1981}}</ref> He later married Susy Feldman,<ref name=\"telegraph19810411\" /> and lived in [[El Lago, Texas]], a suburb of Houston.\n\nYoung died on January 5, 2018, at his home in Houston of complications from [[pneumonia]]. He was 87.<ref name=\"nyt20180106\"/><ref name=\"nasa20180106\">{{cite web |title=NASA Remembers Agency's Most Experienced Astronaut |url=https://www.nasa.gov/press-release/nasa-remembers-agency-s-most-experienced-astronaut |publisher=NASA |date=January 6, 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180106201553/https://www.nasa.gov/press-release/nasa-remembers-agency-s-most-experienced-astronaut/ |archivedate=January 6, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"collect20180106\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.collectspace.com/news/news-010618a-astronaut-john-young-obituary.html |title=John Young, ninth astronaut on moon, led first shuttle mission, dies at 87 |work=[[collectSPACE]] |date=January 6, 2018 |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\n===Military and NASA insignia and decorations===\n* [[China Service Medal]] (1953)\n* [[Korean Service Medal]] with two [[battle stars]] (1953)\n* [[National Defense Service Medal]] with star (1953, 1966)\n* [[United Nations Korea Medal]] (1953)\n* [[Astronaut badge#U.S. Navy, Marine Corps, and Coast Guard astronauts|Navy Astronaut Wings]] (1965)<ref name=\"bio\" /><ref name=\"hist.recip.list\">{{cite web |url=https://searchpub.nssc.nasa.gov/servlet/sm.web.Fetch/Agency_Awards_Historical_Recipient_List.pdf?rhid=1000&did=2120817&type=released |title=Historical Recipient List |publisher=NASA |accessdate=January 8, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Distinguished Service Medal (United States Navy)|Navy Distinguished Service Medal]] with [[5/16 inch star|gold award star]] (1969, 1972)<ref name=\"bio\" /><ref name=\"hist.recip.list\" />\n* [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)|Distinguished Flying Cross]] with two gold award stars<ref name=\"bio\" />\n* [[Congressional Space Medal of Honor]] (1981)<ref name=\"bio\" /><ref name=\"hist.recip.list\" />\n* [[NASA Distinguished Service Medal]] (1969) with three [[oak leaf cluster]]s (1981, 2004)<ref name=\"bio\" />\n* [[NASA Exceptional Achievement Medal]] (1994)<ref name=\"hist.recip.list\" />\n* [[NASA Exceptional Engineering Achievement Medal]] (1988)<ref name=\"bio\" /><ref name=\"hist.recip.list\" />\n* [[NASA Exceptional Service Medal]] (1965, 1966, 2006)<ref name=\"hist.recip.list\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.johnwyoung.com/bio/award-esm.htm |title=Biography: 2 Exceptional Service Medals |work=JohnWYoung.org |access-date=May 14, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[NASA Outstanding Leadership Medal]] (1992)<ref name=\"bio\" /><ref name=\"hist.recip.list\" />\n* [[NASA Space Flight Medal]] (1981, 1983)<ref name=\"hist.recip.list\" />\n\n==Awards and honors==\n[[File:20-02-001-aviation.jpg|thumb|right|Plaque of Young at the [[Georgia Aviation Hall of Fame]]]]\n\n* Inducted into six Aviation and Astronaut Halls of Fame<ref name=\"bio\" />\n* General [[James E. Hill]] Lifetime Space Achievement Award<ref>{{cite web |url=http://2010.nationalspacesymposium.org/node/580.html |title=The General James E. Hill Lifetime Space Achievement Award |publisher=National Space Symposium |date=2010 |access-date=May 14, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130615164321/http://2010.nationalspacesymposium.org/node/580.html |archivedate=June 15, 2013 }}</ref> from the [[Space Foundation]] (2010)<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://2010.nationalspacesymposium.org/media/press-releases/legendary-astronaut-john-young-to-receive-general-james-e-hill-lifetime-space-a.html |title=Legendary Astronaut John Young to Receive General James E. Hill Lifetime Space Achievement Award |publisher=National Space Symposium |first=Janet |last=Stevens |date=January 22, 2010 |access-date=May 14, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130615164322/http://2010.nationalspacesymposium.org/media/press-releases/legendary-astronaut-john-young-to-receive-general-james-e-hill-lifetime-space-a.html |archivedate=June 15, 2013 }}</ref>\n* Exceptional Engineering Achievement Award (1985)<ref name=\"bio\" />\n* [[Academy of Achievement|Golden Plate Award]] for Science and Exploration (1993)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.achievement.org/our-history/golden-plate-awards/all-honorees/ |title=Golden Plate Awardees listed by year |publisher=Academy of Achievement |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[American Astronautical Society]] Space Flight Award (1993)<ref name=\"bio\" />\n*In 1995, Young was inducted into the [[International Air & Space Hall of Fame]] at the [[San Diego Air & Space Museum]].<ref>Sprekelmeyer, Linda, editor. ''These We Honor: The International Aerospace Hall of Fame''. Donning Co. Publishers, 2006. {{ISBN|978-1-57864-397-4}}.</ref>\n*In 2001, Young was inducted into the [[Georgia Aviation Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Captain John W. Young |url=http://www.gaaviationhalloffame.com/Hall-of-Fame.48.0.html?avid=93 |access-date=October 9, 2018 |website=Georgia Aviation Hall of Fame}}</ref>\n* NASA Ambassador of Exploration (2005)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/centers/johnson/news/releases/H05-192.html |title=NASA Names Astronaut John Young Ambassador of Exploration |publisher=NASA |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n* He was the first John Young History Maker Honoree in 2005<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cflhistory.org/cflhistory.org/wp-content/uploads/2017-John-Young-History-Maker-Sponsorship-Package.pdf |title=11th Annual John Young History Maker Celebration |publisher=Historical Society of Central Florida |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n* Six [[Honorary degree|honorary]] doctorate degrees<ref name=\"bio\" />\n* [[Florida State Road 423|John Young Parkway]], a major highway in [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]] and [[Kissimmee, Florida]], is named for him. When he heard the highway was named for him, he said \"Them boys shouldn't a'done that. I ain't dead yet\".<ref name=\"sts61\" /> An elementary school ([[Orange County Public Schools|OCPS]]) on the parkway also bears his name.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://johnyounges.ocps.net/ |title=John Young Elementary School Homepage |access-date=January 6, 2018 |publisher=John Young Elementary School}}</ref>\n* The planetarium at the [[Orlando Science Center]] was originally named in his honor.<ref name=\"orsent19901028\">{{cite news |url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1990-10-28/news/9010240091_1_telescope-science-center-planets |title=Where Stargazers Can Get The Big Picture |work=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |first=Cindy |last=Schreuder |date=October 28, 1990 |access-date=May 14, 2013}}</ref>\n*Ranked as the No. 3 most-popular space hero in a 2010 [[Space Foundation]] survey<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.spacefoundation.org/news/space-foundation-survey-reveals-broad-range-space-heroes-early-astronauts-still-most |title=Space Foundation Survey Reveals Broad Range of Space Heroes; Early Astronauts Still the Most Inspirational |publisher=Space Foundation |first=Carol |last=Hively |date=October 27, 2010 |access-date=May 14, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180107174826/https://www.spacefoundation.org/news/space-foundation-survey-reveals-broad-range-space-heroes-early-astronauts-still-most |archive-date=January 7, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* Recipient of ''[[Aviation Week]]''{{'}}s 1998 [[Philip J. Klass]] Award for Lifetime Achievement<ref>{{cite web |url=https://laureates.aviationweek.com/en/winners/previous-winners.html |title=Aviation Week's Laureate Awards Past Winners |access-date=January 6, 2018 |publisher=Aviation Week}}</ref>\n* Asteroid [[5362 Johnyoung]] was named in his memory in 2018\n\nAlong with nine other Gemini astronauts, Young was inducted into the [[International Space Hall of Fame]] in 1982.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28841417/albuquerque_journal/ |title=Astronauts Laud Gemini as Precursor to Shuttle |last1=Shay |first1=Erin |newspaper=Albuquerque Journal |location=Albuquerque, New Mexico |date=October 3, 1982 |page=3 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Young, along with the other 12 Gemini astronauts, was inducted into the second [[U.S. Astronaut Hall of Fame]] class in 1993.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/33582881/florida_today/ |title=Activities Honor Gemini Astronauts |newspaper=Florida Today |location=Cocoa, Florida |date=March 14, 1993 |page=41 |via=Newspapers.com |last1=Clark |first1=Amy}}</ref>\n\n===Organizations===\n* [[American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics]] [[fellow]]<ref name=\"johnwyoung.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.johnwyoung.com/bio/org.htm |title=Biography: Organization Memberships |work=JohnWYoung.org |access-date=May 14, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"bio\" />\n* American Astronautical Society fellow<ref name=\"johnwyoung.com\" /><ref name=\"bio\" />\n* [[Society of Experimental Test Pilots]] fellow<ref name=\"johnwyoung.com\" /><ref name=\"bio\" />\n* [[Tau Beta Pi]] Engineering Honor Society member<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tbp.org/about/Dist/Astronauts.cfm |title=Astronauts and Scientists |access-date=January 6, 2018 |publisher=Tau Beta Pi}}</ref>\n* [[Sigma Gamma Tau]] Aerospace Engineering Honor Society member<ref name=\"bio\" />\n* Georgia Tech [[ANAK Society]] member<ref>{{cite book |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Kp5sCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA26&lpg=PA26&dq=georgia+tech+anak+society+john+young&source=bl&ots=xmFrxa_pFd&sig=iqN7YnTgt_4jKESg5JfKT9eC0RQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjji5297cTYAhWGvVMKHXLKDCkQ6AEIPzAD#v=onepage&q=georgia%20tech%20anak%20society%20john%20young&f=false |title=Secret Societies Vol. 3: The Collegiate Secret Societies of America |last1=Francis |first1=Arthur Morius |page=26 |chapter=2 |publisher=Lulu.com |date=February 20, 2015 |access-date=January 6, 2018}}{{self-published source|date=February 2020}}</ref>{{self-published inline|date=February 2020}}\n* [[Sigma Chi]] fraternity member<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sigmachi.org/the-sigma-chi-museum |publisher=Sigma Chi Fraternity |title=The Sigma Chi Museum |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, [[Northrop Grumman]] announced that the [[Cygnus spacecraft]] for their tenth cargo resupply mission to the [[International Space Station]] would be named S.S. ''John Young''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.space.com/42250-cygnus-cargo-ship-apollo-john-young.html |title=Space Station-Bound Cargo Ship Named for Moonwalker John Young |work=Space.com |last=Pearlman |first=Robert Z. |date=October 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Florida State Road 423]] is named in his honor, as is [[Orange County Public Schools|John Young Elementary School]] in Orlando, Florida.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Volz |first1=Brianna |title=Astronaut John Young, who grew up in Orlando, dies at 87 |url=https://www.clickorlando.com/news/space-news/astronaut-john-young-dies-at-87 |accessdate=January 24, 2019 |work=WKMG |date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Scott Kelly (astronaut)|Scott Kelly]] (an American astronaut who [[ISS year long mission|spent nearly a year aboard the International Space Station]]) had high praise for Young in his memoir, ''[[Endurance: A Year in Space, a Lifetime of Discovery]]''. Upon learning that Young would interview him as part of his astronaut selection process, Kelly listed some of Young's more impressive achievements, and then stated simply, \"He was what you might call an astronaut's astronaut, a living legend. I wanted to be just like him.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Kelly |first=Scott |others=With Margaret Lazarus Dean |title=Endurance: A Year in Space, a Lifetime of Discovery |title-link=Endurance: A Year in Space, a Lifetime of Discovery |publisher=Alfred A. Knopf, a division of Penguin Random House |year=2017 |page=201 |isbn=9781524731595}}</ref>\n\n==In media==\nIn the 1995 film ''[[Apollo 13 (film)|Apollo 13]]'', Young was played by Ben Marley.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0112384/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast |title=Apollo 13, Full Cast and Crew |publisher=IMDb |access-date=December 5, 2017}}</ref> In the 1998 [[HBO]] [[miniseries]], ''[[From the Earth to the Moon (miniseries)|From the Earth to the Moon]]'', he was played by [[John Posey (actor)|John Posey]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0120570/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast |title=From the Earth to the Moon, Full Cast and Crew |publisher=IMDb |access-date=December 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\nYoung is one of the astronauts featured in the 2007 documentary film and book ''[[In the Shadow of the Moon (2007 film)|In the Shadow of the Moon]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0925248/fullcredits#cast |title=In the Shadow of the Moon: Full Cast and Crew |publisher=IMDb |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> the 2007 documentary film ''[[The Wonder of It All (2007 film)|The Wonder of It All]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0928406/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast |title=The Wonder of It All: Full Cast and Crew |publisher=IMDb |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> and the 2008 Discovery Channel series ''[[When We Left Earth: The NASA Missions|When We Left Earth]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1233514/fullcredits |title=When We Left Earth: Full Cast and Crew |publisher=IMDb |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nYoung's voice during the STS-1 mission can be heard in the song \"[[Countdown (Rush song)|Countdown]]\" by [[Rush (band)|Rush]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Spaceflight}}\n*[[List of spaceflight records]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |last=Thompson |first=Neal |authorlink=Neal Thompson |title=Light This Candle: The Life & Times of Alan Shepard, America's First Spaceman |edition=1st |date=2004 |publisher=Crown Publishers |location=New York |isbn=0-609-61001-5 |oclc=52631310 |lccn=2003015688 |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/lightthiscandlel00thom }}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[http://www.chron.com/news/nation-world/article/Conversation-With-John-Young-1563092.php \"Conversation With John Young\"], ''Houston Chronicle'' (December 17, 2004)\n*[http://www.balettie.com/young/ \"The Big Picture: Ways to Mitigate or Prevent Very Bad Planet Earth Events\"], an essay by Young\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{C-SPAN|johnyoung04}}\n*{{IMDb name|0974135}}\n*{{Find a Grave|186428895}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Alan Shepard]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Chief of the Astronaut Office]]\n|years=1974\u20131987}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Daniel Brandenstein]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{People who have traveled to the Moon}}\n{{NASA Astronaut Group 2}}\n{{Gemini program}}\n{{Congressional Space Medal of Honor}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Young, John}}\n<!--Categories-->\n[[Category:John Young| ]]\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:1965 in spaceflight]]\n[[Category:1966 in spaceflight]]\n[[Category:1969 in spaceflight]]\n[[Category:1972 in spaceflight]]\n[[Category:1981 in spaceflight]]\n[[Category:1983 in spaceflight]]\n[[Category:Apollo 10]]\n[[Category:Apollo 16]]\n[[Category:American astronauts]]\n[[Category:Aviators from California]]\n[[Category:Apollo program astronauts]]\n[[Category:People who have walked on the Moon]]\n[[Category:American aerospace engineers]]\n[[Category:United States Navy astronauts]]\n[[Category:NASA civilian astronauts]]\n[[Category:United States Astronaut Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:People from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Georgia Tech alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Test Pilot School alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Navy officers]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Aviators]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from California]]\n[[Category:National Aviation Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:American naval personnel of the Korean War]]\n[[Category:American test pilots]]\n[[Category:NASA people]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Congressional Space Medal of Honor]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Navy Distinguished Service Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the NASA Distinguished Service Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the NASA Exceptional Achievement Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the NASA Exceptional Service Medal]]\n[[Category:American autobiographers]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Toastmasters members]]\n[[Category:Aviators from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Aviators from Florida]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Florida]]\n[[Category:People from Orlando, Florida]]\n[[Category:Project Gemini astronauts]]\n[[Category:Space Shuttle program astronauts]]\n[[Category:Burials at Arlington National Cemetery]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = John Watts Young\n| image         = Astronaut John W. Young.jpg\n| caption       =\n| nationality   = American\n| birth_name    = John Watts Young\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date|1930|09|24}}\n| birth_place   = [[San Francisco, California]], U.S.\n| death_date    = {{Death date and age|2018|01|05|1930|09|24}}\n| death_place   = [[Seabrook, Texas]] U.S.\n| occupation    = [[United States Naval Aviator|Naval Aviator]], [[test pilot]]\n| alma_mater    = [[Georgia Institute of Technology]], B.S. 1952\n| module        = {{Infobox astronaut|child =yes\n| type          = [[NASA]] astronaut\n| rank          = {{Dodseal|USNO6|25}} [[Captain (United States O-6)|Captain]], [[United States Navy|USN]]\n| selection     = [[List of astronauts by year of selection#1962|1962 NASA Group 2]]\n| time          = 34d 19h 39m\n| eva1          = 3\n| eva2          = 20h 14m 14s\n| mission       = [[Gemini 3]], [[Gemini 10]], [[Apollo 10]], [[Apollo 16]], [[STS-1]], [[STS-9]]\n| insignia      = [[File:Gemini3.png|45px]] [[File:Gemini 10 Insignia.svg|54px]] [[File:Apollo-10-LOGO.png|45px]] [[File:Apollo-16-LOGO.png|45px]] [[File:Sts-1-patch.png|45px]] [[File:Sts-9-patch.png|45px]]\n| Date of ret   = December 31, 2004\n| awards        = [[File:Dfc-usa.jpg|20px|link=Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)]] {{CS Medal of Honor}} [[File:NASA Distinguished Service Medal.jpg|20px|link=NASA Distinguished Service Medal]]\n}}}}\n\n'''John Watts Young''' (September 24, 1930&nbsp;\u2013 January 5, 2018) was an American [[astronaut]], [[United States Navy|naval officer]] and [[United States Naval Aviator|aviator]], [[test pilot]], and [[aerospace engineering|aeronautical engineer]]. He became the [[List of Apollo astronauts#People who have walked on the Moon|ninth person to walk on the Moon]] as Commander of the [[Apollo 16]] mission in 1972. Young enjoyed the longest career of any astronaut, becoming the first person to fly six space missions over the course of 42 years of active [[NASA]] service.<ref name=\"bio\">{{cite web |url=http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/Bios/htmlbios/young.html |title=Biographical Data: John W. Young (Captain, USN Ret.) |publisher=NASA |date=August 2010 |access-date=May 14, 2013}}</ref> He is the only person to have piloted and commanded four different classes of spacecraft: [[Project Gemini|Gemini]], the [[Apollo Command and Service Module]], the [[Apollo Lunar Module]], and the [[Space Shuttle]].<ref name=\"sentinel20160924\">{{cite news |last1=Speck |first1=Emilee |title=Moon-walking astronaut John Young turned 86 on Saturday |url=http://www.orlandosentinel.com/news/space/go-for-launch/os-nasa-astronaut-john-young-turns-86-20160923-story.html |access-date=August 16, 2017 |work=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |date=September 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 1965 Young flew on the [[Gemini 3|first crewed Gemini mission]], and then commanded the 1966 [[Gemini 10]] mission. In 1969 during [[Apollo 10]], he became the first person to fly solo around the Moon.<ref name=\"nasa200412007\">{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/vision/space/features/young_retires.html |title=From Gemini to Shuttle: John Young Retires |publisher=NASA |date=December 7, 2004 |access-date=January 7, 2018}}</ref> He then walked on the Moon and drove the [[Lunar Roving Vehicle]] on the Moon's surface during [[Apollo 16]], and is one of only three people to have [[List of Apollo astronauts|flown to the Moon]] twice.<ref name=\"npr20180106\">{{cite news |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2017/01/16/505928876/gene-cernan-last-man-to-walk-on-the-moon-dies-at-82 |title=Gene Cernan, Last Man To Walk On The Moon, Dies At 82 |publisher=NPR |last1=Lewis |first1=Russell |date=January 6, 2018 |access-date=January 7, 2018}}</ref> \n\nYoung also commanded two flights of [[Space Shuttle Columbia|Space Shuttle ''Columbia'']]: [[STS-1]] in 1981, the [[Space Shuttle]] program's first launch, and [[STS-9]] in 1983. Young served as [[Chief of the Astronaut Office]] from 1974 to 1987, and retired from NASA in 2004.\n\n==Early years and education==\nYoung was born in [[San Francisco, California]], on September 24, 1930,<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28981374/the_orlando_sentinel/ |title=Astronauts Could Have a Party |newspaper=The Orlando Sentinel |location=Orlando, Florida |date=February 3, 1963 |page=15 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> to parents William Hugh Young, a civil engineer,<ref name=\"nyt20180106\">{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/06/obituaries/john-young-dead.html |title=John Young, Who Led First Space Shuttle Mission, Dies at 87 |work=[[The New York Times]] |first=Richard |last=Goldstein |date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> and Wanda Howland Young.<ref name=\"navy-history-young\">{{cite web |url=http://www.history.navy.mil/research/histories/biographies-list/bios-y/Young-John/Young-John-Text.html |title=John Watts Young |publisher=Navy Office of Information, Biographies Branch |date=April 10, 1972}}</ref> At 18 months old, due to the [[Great Depression]], he moved with his family to [[Cartersville, Georgia|Cartersville]], [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]],<ref name=\"fortune20180106\">{{cite news |url=http://amp.timeinc.net/fortune/2018/01/06/astronaut-john-young-dead |title=Astronaut John Young, One of Only 12 to Walk on Moon, Dies at 87 |work=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]] |agency=[[Bloomberg News]] |date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> then to [[Orlando, Florida]], where he attended grade school and later [[Orange County Public Schools#High schools|Orlando High School]] until graduating in 1948.<ref name=\"sjg19650324\">{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=HhpdAAAAIBAJ&pg=1598%2C4411712 |title=John Young, as Early as 1946, Displayed Interest in Rockets |work=[[St. Joseph Gazette]] |agency=Associated Press |volume=120 |issue=238 |page=6A |date=March 24, 1965 |access-date=May 14, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"jwy-edu\">{{cite web |url=http://www.johnwyoung.org/bio/education.htm |title=Biography: Education |work=JohnWYoung.org |access-date=May 14, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061128151906/http://www.johnwyoung.org/bio/education.htm |archive-date=November 28, 2006 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Young was a [[Scouts BSA (Boy Scouts of America)|Boy Scout]] and earned the rank of [[Second Class (Boy Scouts of America)|Second Class]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scouting.org/About/FactSheets/scouting_space.aspx |title=Scouting and Space Exploration |website=Scouting.org |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303213130/http://www.scouting.org/about/factsheets/scouting_space.aspx |archivedate=March 3, 2016 }}</ref>\n\nYoung earned a [[Bachelor of Science]] degree with highest honors in [[Aerospace engineering|Aeronautical Engineering]] from the [[Georgia Institute of Technology]] in 1952; while attending, he became a member of the national military honor society [[Scabbard and Blade]] and [[Sigma Chi]] fraternity.<ref name=\"fw4465\">{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1774&dat=19650404&id=AZscAAAAIBAJ&pg=5001,1212947 |title=Virgil Grissom and John Young: Our Trail-Blazing \"Twin\" Astronauts |work=[[Sarasota Herald-Tribune]] |series=Family Weekly |first=John W. |last=Wasik |page=4 |date=April 4, 1965 |access-date=January 28, 2010}}</ref><ref name=\"blueprint1952\">{{cite book |url=http://hdl.handle.net/1853/25833 |title=Blue Print |publisher=[[Georgia Institute of Technology]] |editor-first=Blount |editor-last=Boswell |volume=45 |page=108 |date=1952}}</ref>\n\n==Navy service==\n{{quote box|align=right|width=28%|quote=I got a telegram from the [[Chief of Naval Operations]] asking me not to do this anymore.|salign=right|source=\u2014Young, describing an air-to-air missile test in which he and another pilot approached each other at Mach 3 - risking destruction of both aircraft.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.johnwyoung.org/bio/navycareer.htm |title=Astronaut John W. Young - Navy Career |website=Johnwyoung.org}}</ref>}}\n\nAfter graduating from [[Georgia Institute of Technology|Georgia Tech]] in 1952, Young entered the [[United States Navy]] through the [[Naval Reserve Officers Training Corps|Navy ROTC]] and was commissioned on June 6, 1952, as an [[ensign (rank)|ensign]].<ref name=\"navy-history-young\" /> He served as fire control officer on the destroyer {{USS|Laws|DD-558|6}} until June 1953 and completed a tour in the [[Sea of Japan]] during the [[Korean War]]. Following this assignment, he was sent to flight training. In January 1954, he was designated a Navy helicopter pilot.<ref name=\"navy-history-young\" /> After receiving his [[United States Naval Aviator|aviator wings]] on December 20, 1954, he was assigned to Fighter Squadron 103 ([[VFA-103|VF-103]]) for four years, flying [[Grumman F9F Cougar]]s from {{USS|Coral Sea|CV-43|6}} and [[Vought F8U Crusader]]s from {{USS|Forrestal|CV-59|6}}.<ref name=\"nmmuseum\" />\n\nAfter training at the [[United States Naval Test Pilot School]] in 1959 with the Class 23, Young was assigned to the Naval Air Test Center at [[Naval Air Station Patuxent River]], Maryland, for three years. His test projects included evaluations of the [[Vought XF8U-3 Crusader III|XF8U-3 Crusader III]] and [[McDonnell Douglas F-4 Phantom II|F-4 Phantom II]] fighter weapons systems. In 1962, he set two world time-to-climb records while flying his Phantom II, attaining {{convert|3000|m|ft|0|sp=us}} from a standing start in 34.52 seconds and {{convert|25000|m|ft|0|sp=us}} from a standing start in 227.6 seconds.<ref name=\"navy-history-young\" /> He also served as maintenance officer of Fighter Squadron 143 ([[VFA-143|VF-143]]) from April to September 1962.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nFellow astronaut [[Charles Bolden]] described Young and [[Robert L. Gibson|Robert \"Hoot\" Gibson]] as the two best pilots he had met during his aviation career: \"Never met two people like them. Everyone else gets into an airplane; John and Hoot wear their airplane. They're just awesome\".<ref name=\"bolden20040106\">{{cite interview |title=Charles F. Bolden |date=January 6, 2004 |access-date=January 6, 2014 |last=Bolden |first=Charles F. |subjectlink=Charles Bolden |interviewer1=Johnson, Sandra |interviewer2=Wright, Rebecca |interviewer3=Ross-Nazzal, Jennifer |work=NASA Johnson Space Center Oral History Project |location=Houston, Texas |url=http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/history/oral_histories/BoldenCF/BoldenCF_1-6-04.htm}}</ref> Young retired from the Navy as a [[Captain (naval)|Captain]] in September 1976, after 25 years.<ref name=\"nmmuseum\">{{cite web |url=http://www.nmspacemuseum.org/halloffame/detail.php?id=70 |title=Commanded the first shuttle flight, the first person to enter space six times |publisher=New Mexico Museum of Space History |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==NASA career==\n===Project Gemini===\n{{Main|Gemini 3|Gemini 10}}\n[[File:Astronaut John Young gemini 3.jpg|left|thumb|Young, age 34, as pilot of Gemini 3]]\nJoining [[NASA]] in 1962, Young was the first of the [[NASA Astronaut Group 2|Astronaut Group 2]] to fly in space, replacing [[Thomas P. Stafford]] as pilot of [[Gemini 3]] when [[Alan Shepard]], the original command pilot, was grounded due to [[M\u00e9ni\u00e8re's disease]].{{sfn|Thompson|2004|p=366}} Making the first crewed flight of the Gemini spacecraft with [[Gus Grissom]] in 1965, Young scored another space first by smuggling a corned beef sandwich onto the spacecraft\u2014a feat for which he was reprimanded. Some members of the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. House of Representatives]] were not pleased about the stunt, claiming that Young cost taxpayers millions of dollars by disrupting a scheduled test of space food during the flight.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://gizmodo.com/50-years-ago-nasa-astronauts-smuggled-a-corned-beef-sa-1693431694 |title=50 Years Ago, NASA Astronauts Smuggled a Corned Beef Sandwich Into Space |work=Gizmodo |last1=Zhang |first1=Sarah |date=March 24, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |url=http://www.jsc.nasa.gov/history/mission_trans/GT03_TEC.PDF |title=Composite Air-to-ground and Onboard Voice Tape Transcription of the GT-3 Mission |publisher=National Astronautics and Space Administration |page=45 |date=April 1965 |access-date=May 14, 2013}}</ref>\n\nYoung then trained as backup pilot for [[Gemini 6A]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/multimedia/imagegallery/image_feature_1010.html |title=Gemini 6 Back-up Crew |publisher=NASA |date=March 23, 2008 |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> The assignment of [[Gemini 7]] backup command pilot [[Ed White (astronaut)|Ed White]] to Apollo, created an opening for Young as commander of [[Gemini 10]] in 1966.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MYasNyKQIxMC&pg=PA151&lpg=PA151 |title=Foothold in the Heavens: The Seventies |series=A History of Human Space Exploration |publisher=[[Springer Science+Business Media]] |last1=Evans |first1=Ben |page=151 |date=August 14, 2010 |isbn=978-1-4419-6341-3 |doi=10.1007/978-1-4419-6342-0}}</ref> The mission was the first to perform a rendezvous with two [[Agena target vehicle]]s; and his pilot, [[Michael Collins (astronaut)|Michael Collins]], performed two spacewalks.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.space.com/37527-gemini-10-photos.html |title=Gemini 10: NASA's Epic 1st Double Rendezvous Mission in Photos |work=Space.com |last1=Lunsford |first1=Christine |date=September 18, 2017 |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://nssdc.gsfc.nasa.gov/nmc/spacecraft/display.action?id=1966-066A |title=Gemini 10 |publisher=NASA Space Science Data Coordinated Archive |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Apollo program===\n{{Main|Apollo 10|Apollo 16}}\n[[File:John W. Young on the Moon.jpg|right|thumb|Young jumps while saluting the [[Lunar Flag Assembly|American flag]] during Apollo 16]]\nIn 1966, Young was assigned to an Apollo crew as [[Apollo Command/Service Module|Command Module]] pilot, with Commander [[Thomas P. Stafford|Thomas Stafford]] and [[Apollo Lunar Module|Lunar Module]] pilot [[Eugene Cernan]]. This crew was assigned as backup to the second crewed Apollo mission, planned before the [[Apollo 1]] fire. After that fire, both crews{{clarify|date=March 2019}} were assigned to the first actual crewed mission, [[Apollo 7]], which flew in October 1968.<ref name=\"bio\" /> In May 1969, this crew flew to the Moon on [[Apollo 10]]. While Stafford and Cernan flew the Lunar Module in lunar orbit for the first time, Young flew the Command Module solo. Apollo 10 set the record for the highest speed attained by any crewed vehicle at {{convert|39897|km/h|mph}} during its return to Earth on May 26, 1969.<ref name=\"Guinness2012\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=biWfNzQiR8EC&pg=PA322 |title=Guinness World Records 2012 |publisher=[[Bantam Books]] |editor-first=Craig |editor-last=Glenday |page=322 |date=2012 |isbn=978-0-345-53437-8}}</ref><ref name=\"Lloyd2010\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uCgRY6llQpYC&pg=PA280 |title=QI: The Book of General Ignorance |publisher=[[Faber and Faber]] |first1=John |last1=Lloyd |first2=John |last2=Mitchinson |edition=The Noticeably Stouter |page=280 |date=2010 |isbn=978-0-571-27378-2}}</ref>\n\nYoung was backup commander of [[Apollo 13]], the troubled mission in which the Moon landing was aborted because of an explosion in the Service Module.<ref name=\"backup\">{{cite web |url=https://airandspace.si.edu/explore-and-learn/topics/apollo/apollo-program/landing-missions/apollo13-crew.cfm |title=Apollo 13 Crew |publisher=Smithsonian National Air and Space Museum |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBy rotation, Young became commander of [[Apollo 16]], and studied [[geology]] with his crew while preparing for the mission.<ref name=sudburytraining>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=s-9UAAAAIBAJ&pg=1178,849265&dq=apollo+16+training&hl=en |title=Astronauts training in Ont. |agency=[[The Canadian Press]] |newspaper=[[Leader-Post|The Leader-Post]] |location=Regina, Saskatchewan |last=Dickie |first=Allan |date=July 7, 1971 |accessdate=November 26, 2011}}</ref> Apollo 16's lunar landing was almost aborted when a malfunction was detected in the SPS engine control system in the Service Module. It was determined that the problem could be worked around, and the mission continued.<ref name=overview>{{cite web |title=Descartes Surprise |url=http://www.hq.nasa.gov/alsj/a16/a16.summary.html |publisher=Apollo Lunar Surface Journal |accessdate=November 26, 2011}}</ref> On the surface, Young took three moonwalks in the [[Descartes Highlands]] with [[Charles Duke]] on April 21, 22 and 23, 1972, making Young the ninth person to walk on the surface of the Moon, while [[Ken Mattingly]] flew the Command Module in lunar orbit.<ref name=\"bio\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/mission_pages/apollo/missions/apollo16.html |title=Apollo 16 |date=July 8, 2009 |publisher=NASA |access-date=January 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\nYoung's final assignment in Apollo was as the backup commander for Cernan on [[Apollo 17]]. The backup crew was originally the [[Apollo 15]] crew, but [[Deke Slayton]] removed them from the assignment when he learned they had taken a small statue to the Moon, as well as stamps that they sold to a dealer.<ref name=15backup>{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=kAsUAAAAIBAJ&pg=5667,8302&dq=apollo+17+backup+crew&hl=en |title=Apollo crew warned about commercialism |newspaper=The Free Lance-Star |date=August 1, 1972 |accessdate=August 26, 2011}}</ref><ref name=nasmcrew>{{cite web |url=http://www.nasm.si.edu/collections/imagery/apollo/as17/a17crew.htm |title=Apollo 17 Crew |work=The Apollo Program |publisher=[[National Air and Space Museum]] |location=Washington, D.C. |accessdate=August 26, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Space Shuttle program===\n{{Main|STS-1|STS-9}}\nIn January 1973 Young was made Chief of the Space Shuttle Branch of the Astronaut Office. In January 1974, he became Chief of the Astronaut Office after the retirement of [[Alan Shepard]].<ref name=\"asf\">{{cite web |url=https://astronautscholarship.org/Astronauts/john-w-young/ |title=John Young |publisher=Astronaut Scholarship Foundation |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nYoung flew two missions of the Space Shuttle, both aboard the {{OV|Columbia}}. He commanded the program's 1981 maiden orbital flight, [[STS-1]], and in 1983 commanded [[STS-9]], which carried the first [[Spacelab]] module.<ref name=\"asf\" /> In 1986 he was in line to make a record seventh space flight on [[Canceled Space Shuttle missions#Canceled due to the Challenger disaster|STS-61-J]] to deploy the [[Hubble Space Telescope]], but the [[Space Shuttle Challenger disaster|Space Shuttle ''Challenger'' disaster]] earlier that year had delayed NASA's schedule.<ref name=\"sts61\">{{cite web |url=http://www.astronautix.com/flights/sts61j.htm |title=STS-61-J |publisher=Encyclopedia Astronautica |date=November 17, 2007 |accessdate=March 31, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100108041720/http://astronautix.com/flights/sts61j.htm |archivedate=January 8, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nYoung was openly critical of NASA management following the ''Challenger'' disaster,<ref>{{cite news |url=http://abcnews.go.com/Technology/wireStory/nasa-legendary-astronaut-moonwalker-john-young-died-52180080 |title=NASA: Legendary astronaut, moonwalker John Young has died |last1=Dunn |first1=Marcia |publisher=ABC News |date=January 6, 2018 |access-date=January 6, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180106202306/http://abcnews.go.com/Technology/wireStory/nasa-legendary-astronaut-moonwalker-john-young-died-52180080 |archive-date=January 6, 2018 |url-status=dead}}</ref> and in April 1987 was made Special Assistant to JSC Director [[Aaron Cohen (Deputy NASA administrator)|Aaron Cohen]] for Engineering, Operations and Safety.<ref name=\"bio\" /> NASA denied that his criticism triggered the move, although Young and industry insiders believed that was the reason for the reassignment.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1987-04-16/news/mn-711_1_johnson-space-center-in-houston |title=The Nation |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=April 16, 1987 |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://articles.latimes.com/1987-07-30/news/mn-378_1_shuttle-flight |title=Top Astronaut Says NASA Forced Him From Job |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=July 30, 1987 |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> In February 1996, he was assigned as Associate Director (Technical) JSC.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nDuring his NASA career, Young logged more than 15,000 hours of training, mostly in simulators, to prepare for positions on eleven spaceflights in prime and backup crew positions.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\n===Retirement===\n[[File:John Young 2006.jpg|right|thumb|upright|Young at the 25th anniversary of STS-1 at [[Kennedy Space Center]]]]\nYoung worked for NASA for 42 years and announced his retirement on December 7, 2004. He retired on December 31, 2004, at the age of 74, but continued to attend the Monday Morning Meeting at the Astronaut Office at JSC for several years thereafter.<ref name=\"Fuglesang\">{{Cite book |title=Tretton dygn i rymden efter fjorton \u00e5r p\u00e5 jorden: dagbok fr\u00e5n rymden |trans-title=Thirteen days in space, after fourteen years on earth: a diary from space |language=Swedish |publisher=Albert Bonniers F\u00f6rlag |first=Christer |last=Fuglesang |date=2007 |isbn=978-91-85555-15-4 |oclc=185242561}}</ref> He logged more than 15,275 hours flying time in [[Powered aircraft#Propeller aircraft|props]], [[Jet aircraft|jets]], [[helicopter]]s, and [[Rocket-powered aircraft|rocket jets]]; more than 9,200 hours in [[Northrop T-38 Talon|T-38]]s; and 835 hours in [[spacecraft]] during six space flights.<ref name=\"bio\" />\n\nOn April 12, 2006, Young appeared at the 25th anniversary of the STS-1 launch at the [[Kennedy Space Center Visitor Complex]], along with pilot [[Robert Crippen]]. The two spoke of their experiences during the flight.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://mediaarchive.ksc.nasa.gov/detail.cfm?mediaid=28394 |title=To honor the 25th anniversary ... |publisher=NASA |first=Jeanne |last=Ryba |date=April 7, 2006 |access-date=October 6, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100531211821/http://mediaarchive.ksc.nasa.gov/detail.cfm?mediaid=28394 |archivedate=May 31, 2010 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Young published an autobiography, ''Forever Young''.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.upf.com/book.asp?id=YOUNG001 |title=Forever Young: A Life of Adventure in Air and Space |work=University Press of Florida |access-date=May 9, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nYoung married Barbara White of [[Savannah, Georgia]], and they had two children, Sandra and John.<ref name=\"fw4465\" /> They were divorced in 1972 after 16 years of marriage.<ref name=\"telegraph19810411\">{{cite news |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=gKgrAAAAIBAJ&pg=5388%2C2658262 |title=Young: America's old man of space |work=[[Nashua Telegraph]] |agency=Associated Press |volume=113 |issue=36 |page=23 |date=April 11, 1981}}</ref> He later married Susy Feldman,<ref name=\"telegraph19810411\" /> and lived in [[El Lago, Texas]], a suburb of Houston.\n\nYoung died on January 5, 2018, at his home in Houston of complications from [[pneumonia]]. He was 87.<ref name=\"nyt20180106\"/><ref name=\"nasa20180106\">{{cite web |title=NASA Remembers Agency's Most Experienced Astronaut |url=https://www.nasa.gov/press-release/nasa-remembers-agency-s-most-experienced-astronaut |publisher=NASA |date=January 6, 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180106201553/https://www.nasa.gov/press-release/nasa-remembers-agency-s-most-experienced-astronaut/ |archivedate=January 6, 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"collect20180106\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.collectspace.com/news/news-010618a-astronaut-john-young-obituary.html |title=John Young, ninth astronaut on moon, led first shuttle mission, dies at 87 |work=[[collectSPACE]] |date=January 6, 2018 |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Recognition==\n===Military and NASA insignia and decorations===\n* [[China Service Medal]] (1953)\n* [[Korean Service Medal]] with two [[battle stars]] (1953)\n* [[National Defense Service Medal]] with star (1953, 1966)\n* [[United Nations Korea Medal]] (1953)\n* [[Astronaut badge#U.S. Navy, Marine Corps, and Coast Guard astronauts|Navy Astronaut Wings]] (1965)<ref name=\"bio\" /><ref name=\"hist.recip.list\">{{cite web |url=https://searchpub.nssc.nasa.gov/servlet/sm.web.Fetch/Agency_Awards_Historical_Recipient_List.pdf?rhid=1000&did=2120817&type=released |title=Historical Recipient List |publisher=NASA |accessdate=January 8, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[Distinguished Service Medal (United States Navy)|Navy Distinguished Service Medal]] with [[5/16 inch star|gold award star]] (1969, 1972)<ref name=\"bio\" /><ref name=\"hist.recip.list\" />\n* [[Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)|Distinguished Flying Cross]] with two gold award stars<ref name=\"bio\" />\n* [[Congressional Space Medal of Honor]] (1981)<ref name=\"bio\" /><ref name=\"hist.recip.list\" />\n* [[NASA Distinguished Service Medal]] (1969) with three [[oak leaf cluster]]s (1981, 2004)<ref name=\"bio\" />\n* [[NASA Exceptional Achievement Medal]] (1994)<ref name=\"hist.recip.list\" />\n* [[NASA Exceptional Engineering Achievement Medal]] (1988)<ref name=\"bio\" /><ref name=\"hist.recip.list\" />\n* [[NASA Exceptional Service Medal]] (1965, 1966, 2006)<ref name=\"hist.recip.list\" /><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.johnwyoung.com/bio/award-esm.htm |title=Biography: 2 Exceptional Service Medals |work=JohnWYoung.org |access-date=May 14, 2013}}</ref>\n* [[NASA Outstanding Leadership Medal]] (1992)<ref name=\"bio\" /><ref name=\"hist.recip.list\" />\n* [[NASA Space Flight Medal]] (1981, 1983)<ref name=\"hist.recip.list\" />\n\n==Awards and honors==\n[[File:20-02-001-aviation.jpg|thumb|right|Plaque of Young at the [[Georgia Aviation Hall of Fame]]]]\n\n* Inducted into six Aviation and Astronaut Halls of Fame<ref name=\"bio\" />\n* General [[James E. Hill]] Lifetime Space Achievement Award<ref>{{cite web |url=http://2010.nationalspacesymposium.org/node/580.html |title=The General James E. Hill Lifetime Space Achievement Award |publisher=National Space Symposium |date=2010 |access-date=May 14, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130615164321/http://2010.nationalspacesymposium.org/node/580.html |archivedate=June 15, 2013 }}</ref> from the [[Space Foundation]] (2010)<ref>{{cite press release |url=http://2010.nationalspacesymposium.org/media/press-releases/legendary-astronaut-john-young-to-receive-general-james-e-hill-lifetime-space-a.html |title=Legendary Astronaut John Young to Receive General James E. Hill Lifetime Space Achievement Award |publisher=National Space Symposium |first=Janet |last=Stevens |date=January 22, 2010 |access-date=May 14, 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://archive.today/20130615164322/http://2010.nationalspacesymposium.org/media/press-releases/legendary-astronaut-john-young-to-receive-general-james-e-hill-lifetime-space-a.html |archivedate=June 15, 2013 }}</ref>\n* Exceptional Engineering Achievement Award (1985)<ref name=\"bio\" />\n* [[Academy of Achievement|Golden Plate Award]] for Science and Exploration (1993)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.achievement.org/our-history/golden-plate-awards/all-honorees/ |title=Golden Plate Awardees listed by year |publisher=Academy of Achievement |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n* [[American Astronautical Society]] Space Flight Award (1993)<ref name=\"bio\" />\n*In 1995, Young was inducted into the [[International Air & Space Hall of Fame]] at the [[San Diego Air & Space Museum]].<ref>Sprekelmeyer, Linda, editor. ''These We Honor: The International Aerospace Hall of Fame''. Donning Co. Publishers, 2006. {{ISBN|978-1-57864-397-4}}.</ref>\n*In 2001, Young was inducted into the [[Georgia Aviation Hall of Fame]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Captain John W. Young |url=http://www.gaaviationhalloffame.com/Hall-of-Fame.48.0.html?avid=93 |access-date=October 9, 2018 |website=Georgia Aviation Hall of Fame}}</ref>\n* NASA Ambassador of Exploration (2005)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nasa.gov/centers/johnson/news/releases/H05-192.html |title=NASA Names Astronaut John Young Ambassador of Exploration |publisher=NASA |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n* He was the first John Young History Maker Honoree in 2005<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cflhistory.org/cflhistory.org/wp-content/uploads/2017-John-Young-History-Maker-Sponsorship-Package.pdf |title=11th Annual John Young History Maker Celebration |publisher=Historical Society of Central Florida |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n* Six [[Honorary degree|honorary]] doctorate degrees<ref name=\"bio\" />\n* [[Florida State Road 423|John Young Parkway]], a major highway in [[Orlando, Florida|Orlando]] and [[Kissimmee, Florida]], is named for him. When he heard the highway was named for him, he said \"Them boys shouldn't a'done that. I ain't dead yet\".<ref name=\"sts61\" /> An elementary school ([[Orange County Public Schools|OCPS]]) on the parkway also bears his name.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://johnyounges.ocps.net/ |title=John Young Elementary School Homepage |access-date=January 6, 2018 |publisher=John Young Elementary School}}</ref>\n* The planetarium at the [[Orlando Science Center]] was originally named in his honor.<ref name=\"orsent19901028\">{{cite news |url=http://articles.orlandosentinel.com/1990-10-28/news/9010240091_1_telescope-science-center-planets |title=Where Stargazers Can Get The Big Picture |work=[[Orlando Sentinel]] |first=Cindy |last=Schreuder |date=October 28, 1990 |access-date=May 14, 2013}}</ref>\n*Ranked as the No. 3 most-popular space hero in a 2010 [[Space Foundation]] survey<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.spacefoundation.org/news/space-foundation-survey-reveals-broad-range-space-heroes-early-astronauts-still-most |title=Space Foundation Survey Reveals Broad Range of Space Heroes; Early Astronauts Still the Most Inspirational |publisher=Space Foundation |first=Carol |last=Hively |date=October 27, 2010 |access-date=May 14, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180107174826/https://www.spacefoundation.org/news/space-foundation-survey-reveals-broad-range-space-heroes-early-astronauts-still-most |archive-date=January 7, 2018 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n* Recipient of ''[[Aviation Week]]''{{'}}s 1998 [[Philip J. Klass]] Award for Lifetime Achievement<ref>{{cite web |url=https://laureates.aviationweek.com/en/winners/previous-winners.html |title=Aviation Week's Laureate Awards Past Winners |access-date=January 6, 2018 |publisher=Aviation Week}}</ref>\n* Asteroid [[5362 Johnyoung]] was named in his memory in 2018\n\nAlong with nine other Gemini astronauts, Young was inducted into the [[International Space Hall of Fame]] in 1982.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/28841417/albuquerque_journal/ |title=Astronauts Laud Gemini as Precursor to Shuttle |last1=Shay |first1=Erin |newspaper=Albuquerque Journal |location=Albuquerque, New Mexico |date=October 3, 1982 |page=3 |via=Newspapers.com}}</ref> Young, along with the other 12 Gemini astronauts, was inducted into the second [[U.S. Astronaut Hall of Fame]] class in 1993.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/33582881/florida_today/ |title=Activities Honor Gemini Astronauts |newspaper=Florida Today |location=Cocoa, Florida |date=March 14, 1993 |page=41 |via=Newspapers.com |last1=Clark |first1=Amy}}</ref>\n\n===Organizations===\n* [[American Institute of Aeronautics and Astronautics]] [[fellow]]<ref name=\"johnwyoung.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.johnwyoung.com/bio/org.htm |title=Biography: Organization Memberships |work=JohnWYoung.org |access-date=May 14, 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"bio\" />\n* American Astronautical Society fellow<ref name=\"johnwyoung.com\" /><ref name=\"bio\" />\n* [[Society of Experimental Test Pilots]] fellow<ref name=\"johnwyoung.com\" /><ref name=\"bio\" />\n* [[Tau Beta Pi]] Engineering Honor Society member<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tbp.org/about/Dist/Astronauts.cfm |title=Astronauts and Scientists |access-date=January 6, 2018 |publisher=Tau Beta Pi}}</ref>\n* [[Sigma Gamma Tau]] Aerospace Engineering Honor Society member<ref name=\"bio\" />\n* Georgia Tech [[ANAK Society]] member<ref>{{cite book |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Kp5sCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA26&lpg=PA26&dq=georgia+tech+anak+society+john+young&source=bl&ots=xmFrxa_pFd&sig=iqN7YnTgt_4jKESg5JfKT9eC0RQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjji5297cTYAhWGvVMKHXLKDCkQ6AEIPzAD#v=onepage&q=georgia%20tech%20anak%20society%20john%20young&f=false |title=Secret Societies Vol. 3: The Collegiate Secret Societies of America |last1=Francis |first1=Arthur Morius |page=26 |chapter=2 |publisher=Lulu.com |date=February 20, 2015 |access-date=January 6, 2018}}{{self-published source}}</ref>{{self-published inline|date=February 2020}}\n* [[Sigma Chi]] fraternity member<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sigmachi.org/the-sigma-chi-museum |publisher=Sigma Chi Fraternity |title=The Sigma Chi Museum |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, [[Northrop Grumman]] announced that the [[Cygnus spacecraft]] for their tenth cargo resupply mission to the [[International Space Station]] would be named S.S. ''John Young''.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.space.com/42250-cygnus-cargo-ship-apollo-john-young.html |title=Space Station-Bound Cargo Ship Named for Moonwalker John Young |work=Space.com |last=Pearlman |first=Robert Z. |date=October 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Florida State Road 423]] is named in his honor, as is [[Orange County Public Schools|John Young Elementary School]] in Orlando, Florida.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Volz |first1=Brianna |title=Astronaut John Young, who grew up in Orlando, dies at 87 |url=https://www.clickorlando.com/news/space-news/astronaut-john-young-dies-at-87 |accessdate=January 24, 2019 |work=WKMG |date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\n[[Scott Kelly (astronaut) | Scott Kelly]] (an American astronaut who [[ISS year long mission | spent nearly a year aboard the International Space Station]]) had high praise for Young in his memoir, ''[[Endurance: A Year in Space, a Lifetime of Discovery]]''. Upon learning that Young would interview him as part of his astronaut selection process, Kelly listed some of Young's more impressive achievements, and then stated simply, \"He was what you might call an astronaut's astronaut, a living legend. I wanted to be just like him.\"<ref>{{cite book |last=Kelly |first=Scott |others=With Margaret Lazarus Dean |title=Endurance: A Year in Space, a Lifetime of Discovery |title-link=Endurance: A Year in Space, a Lifetime of Discovery |publisher=Alfred A. Knopf, a division of Penguin Random House |year=2017 |page=201 |isbn=9781524731595}}</ref>\n\n==In media==\nIn the 1995 film ''[[Apollo 13 (film)|Apollo 13]]'', Young was played by Ben Marley.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0112384/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast |title=Apollo 13, Full Cast and Crew |publisher=IMDb |access-date=December 5, 2017}}</ref> In the 1998 [[HBO]] [[miniseries]], ''[[From the Earth to the Moon (miniseries)|From the Earth to the Moon]]'', he was played by [[John Posey (actor)|John Posey]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0120570/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast |title=From the Earth to the Moon, Full Cast and Crew |publisher=IMDb |access-date=December 5, 2017}}</ref>\n\nYoung is one of the astronauts featured in the 2007 documentary film and book ''[[In the Shadow of the Moon (2007 film)|In the Shadow of the Moon]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0925248/fullcredits#cast |title=In the Shadow of the Moon: Full Cast and Crew |publisher=IMDb |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> the 2007 documentary film ''[[The Wonder of It All (2007 film)|The Wonder of It All]]'',<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0928406/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast |title=The Wonder of It All: Full Cast and Crew |publisher=IMDb |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref> and the 2008 Discovery Channel series ''[[When We Left Earth: The NASA Missions|When We Left Earth]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt1233514/fullcredits |title=When We Left Earth: Full Cast and Crew |publisher=IMDb |access-date=January 6, 2018}}</ref>\n\nYoung's voice during the STS-1 mission can be heard in the song \"[[Countdown (Rush song)|Countdown]]\" by [[Rush (band)|Rush]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal bar|Biography|Spaceflight}}\n*[[List of spaceflight records]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Bibliography==\n* {{cite book |last=Thompson |first=Neal |authorlink=Neal Thompson |title=Light This Candle: The Life & Times of Alan Shepard, America's First Spaceman |edition=1st |date=2004 |publisher=Crown Publishers |location=New York |isbn=0-609-61001-5 |oclc=52631310 |lccn=2003015688 |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/lightthiscandlel00thom }}\n\n==Further reading==\n*[http://www.chron.com/news/nation-world/article/Conversation-With-John-Young-1563092.php \"Conversation With John Young\"], ''Houston Chronicle'' (December 17, 2004)\n*[http://www.balettie.com/young/ \"The Big Picture: Ways to Mitigate or Prevent Very Bad Planet Earth Events\"], an essay by Young\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n*{{C-SPAN|johnyoung04}}\n*{{IMDb name|0974135}}\n*{{Find a Grave|186428895}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Alan Shepard]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Chief of the Astronaut Office]]\n|years=1974\u20131987}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Daniel Brandenstein]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{People who have traveled to the Moon}}\n{{NASA Astronaut Group 2}}\n{{Gemini program}}\n{{Congressional Space Medal of Honor}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2019}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Young, John}}\n<!--Categories-->\n[[Category:John Young| ]]\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2018 deaths]]\n[[Category:1965 in spaceflight]]\n[[Category:1966 in spaceflight]]\n[[Category:1969 in spaceflight]]\n[[Category:1972 in spaceflight]]\n[[Category:1981 in spaceflight]]\n[[Category:1983 in spaceflight]]\n[[Category:Apollo 10]]\n[[Category:Apollo 16]]\n[[Category:American astronauts]]\n[[Category:Aviators from California]]\n[[Category:Apollo program astronauts]]\n[[Category:People who have walked on the Moon]]\n[[Category:American aerospace engineers]]\n[[Category:United States Navy astronauts]]\n[[Category:NASA civilian astronauts]]\n[[Category:United States Astronaut Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:People from San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Georgia Tech alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Test Pilot School alumni]]\n[[Category:United States Navy officers]]\n[[Category:United States Naval Aviators]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from California]]\n[[Category:National Aviation Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:American naval personnel of the Korean War]]\n[[Category:American test pilots]]\n[[Category:NASA people]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Congressional Space Medal of Honor]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Navy Distinguished Service Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Distinguished Flying Cross (United States)]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the NASA Distinguished Service Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the NASA Exceptional Achievement Medal]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the NASA Exceptional Service Medal]]\n[[Category:American autobiographers]]\n[[Category:Articles containing video clips]]\n[[Category:Toastmasters members]]\n[[Category:Aviators from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Aviators from Florida]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Georgia (U.S. state)]]\n[[Category:Military personnel from Florida]]\n[[Category:People from Orlando, Florida]]\n[[Category:Project Gemini astronauts]]\n[[Category:Space Shuttle program astronauts]]\n[[Category:Burials at Arlington National Cemetery]]\n", "name_user": "Majavah", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Young_(astronaut)"}
{"title_page": "Lida Moser", "text_new": "<br />\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Lida Moser\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1920|8|17|mf=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[New York City]], New York\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2014|8|11|1920|8|17}}\n| death_place        = [[Rockville, MD]]\n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = \n| occupation         = [[Photographer]], [[author]]\n| years_active       = 1947 &mdash; 2014\n| employer           = \n| known_for          = photojournalism, portraiture, fashion, experimental, street photography\n| notable_works      = Judy and the Boys, 1961\n| spouse             = \n| partner            = \n| children           = \n| parents            = \n| awards             = \n| website            = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n'''Lida Moser''' (August 17, 1920 \u2013 August 11, 2014)<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> was an American-born [[photographer]] and [[author]], with a career that spanned more than six decades, before retiring in her 90s. She was known for her photojournalism and [[street photography]] as a member of both the [[Photo League]] <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.higherpictures.com/artists/Women_of_the_Photo_League/Works.aspx?s=190 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-09-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120103043632/http://www.higherpictures.com/artists/Women_of_the_Photo_League/Works.aspx?s=190 |archivedate=2012-01-03 }} | Women of the Photo League</ref> and the New York School. Her portfolio includes black and white commercial, portrait, landscape, experimental, [[Abstraction|abstract,]] and [[documentary photography]], with her work continuing to have an impact.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe Photo League was an early center of American documentary photography in the post war years, with membership including many of the most significant photographers of the 20th century. In a retrospective at the [[Fraser Gallery]] in Washington DC, she was described as a pioneer in the field of photojournalism,<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefrasergallery.com/reviews/LidaMoserWCP2005.html |title=Lida Moser: Fifty Years of Photographs|first=Louis |last=Jacobson |date=8 April 2005 |work=Washington City Paper |accessdate=2012-09-21}}</ref>  and ''The [[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' noted that she \"excelled at photojournalism at a time when women were a rarity in the field.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Slotnik|first=Daniel E.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/03/arts/lida-moser-photographer-with-an-urban-eye-dies-at-93.html|title=Lida Moser, Photographer With an Urban Eye, Dies at 93|date=2014-09-02|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-15|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> She has also been described, much to Moser's annoyance,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/arts/museums-galleries/blog/13081071/why-photographer-lida-moser-couldnt-be-pigeonholed|title=Why Photographer Lida Moser Couldn't Be Pigeonholed|website=Washington City Paper|language=en|access-date=2018-12-19}}</ref> the ''\"grandmother of American photojournalism.\"''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/arts/article/13028481/photographic-memories|title=Photographic Memories|website=Washington City Paper|language=en|access-date=2018-12-19}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Judy and the Boys 1961.jpg|300px|thumb| \"Judy and the Boys (Mimicry)\" Photograph by Lida Moser, 1961.]]\nMoser was born in 1920 in New York City.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/lida-moser-photographer-of-new-york-and-beyond-dies-at-93/2014/08/30/ea3fb98a-2ec3-11e4-9b98-848790384093_story.html|title=Lida Moser, photographer of New York and beyond, dies at 93|author=Emily Langer|date=August 30, 2014|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=March 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Moser|first=Lidia|title=United States Public Records Index|url=https://familysearch.org|publisher=Family Search|accessdate=28 October 2013}}</ref> Her career started in 1947 as an assistant in [[Berenice Abbott|Berenice Abbott's]] studio.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://montrealgazette.com/news/local-news/photojournalist-made-her-mark-in-quebec/|title=Photojournalist made her mark in Quebec|last=Lalonde|first=Michelle|date=2014-04-14|website=The Montreal Gazette|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> She then earned her first assignment from ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' in 1949, traveling across [[Canada]]. Other magazines featuring her work included ''[[Harper's Bazaar]]'', ''[[Look (American magazine)|Look]]'' and ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]''. She authored a number of books of her own work and co-authored several photographic technique books. Articles and ongoing columns appeared in the ''New York Times'', ''New York Sunday Times'', ''Amphoto Guide to Special Effects'', ''Fun in Photography'', ''Career Photography'', ''Women See Men'', ''Women of Vision'' and ''This Was the Photo League'', among others.\n\nIn 1949 Moser was assigned by ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' magazine to travel to Scotland and photograph leading [[List of Scottish writers|Scottish writers]] and artists. Over 100 of those photographs are now in the permanent collection of [[National Galleries of Scotland|The National Galleries of Scotland]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/search|title=Artworks {{!}} National Galleries of Scotland - Lida Moser Search|last=|first=|date=|website=www.nationalgalleries.org|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> Moser photographed key artists and writers such as [[James Bridie|James Birdie]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/108702/james-bridie|title=James Bridie|website=National Galleries of Scotland|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> [[Stanley Cursiter]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/108703/stanley-cursiter-1887-1976-artist-his-studio|title=Stanley Cursiter, 1887 - 1976. Artist in his Studio|website=National Galleries of Scotland|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> [[William Crosbie (artist)|William Crosbie]],<ref name=\":5\" /> [[Hugh MacDiarmid]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/108631/christopher-murray-grieve-nom-de-plume-hugh-macdiarmid-1892-1978-poet|title=Christopher Murray Grieve (nom de plume 'Hugh MacDiarmid'), 1892 - 1978. Poet|website=National Galleries of Scotland|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> [[Sorley MacLean]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/108636/sorley-maclean-1911-1996-poet|title=Sorley MacLean, 1911 - 1996. Poet|website=National Galleries of Scotland|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>[[Anne Redpath]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/108640/anne-redpath-1895-1965-artist|title=Anne Redpath, 1895 - 1965. Artist|website=National Galleries of Scotland|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> [[Benno Schotz]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/108652/benno-schotz-1891-1984-sculptor|title=Benno Schotz, 1891 - 1984. Sculptor|website=National Galleries of Scotland|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> [[Douglas Young (classicist)|Douglas Young]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/108664/douglas-young-1913-1973-poet|title=Douglas Young, 1913 - 1973. Poet|website=National Galleries of Scotland|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>  and many others.\n\nMoser\u2019s series of \"Camera View\" articles on photography for ''The New York Times'' appeared between 1974 and 1981.<ref name=\"cooperative galleries\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thefrasergallery.com/reviews/LidaMoserWCP2005.html |title=A Photographer's Guide to Cooperative Galleries; Cooperative Galleries|first=Lida |last=Moser |date=17 October 1976 |work=New York Times |accessdate=2012-09-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artforum.com/news/lida-moser-1920-2014-48110|title=Lida Moser (1920\u20132014)|website=www.artforum.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> Her photography has fetched as much as $4,000 at Christie's and other auctions<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artnet.com/artists/lida-moser/past-auction-results|title=Past Auction Results for Lida Moser|website= Artnet.com|accessdate=March 25, 2019}}</ref> and continues to be collected and displayed by more than 40 museums worldwide.<ref name=\"NGS\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/search?search=Lida%20Moser|title= Artworks, 115 artworks, Lida Moser|website=National Galleries Scotland|accessdate= March 25, 2019}}</ref> Moser\u2019s relationship to French photographer [[Eug\u00e8ne Atget]] can be seen in her photographs of [[Edinburgh]] as an early influence and that of American photographer [[Walker Evans]].\n\nMoser was a close friend of American artist [[Alice Neel]], and she photographed Neel several times;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bangordailynews.com/2014/09/02/living/noted-photographer-lida-moser-dies-at-93/|title=Noted photographer Lida Moser dies at 93|website=Bangor Daily News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> in return Neel painted multiple portraits of Moser, which now hang is several museums in the U.S.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nAccording to ''The New York Times'', \"Perhaps her most famous photograph, \u201cMimicry ([[:File:Judy and the Boys 1961.jpg|Judy and the Boys]])\u201d (1961), began as a shoot for an aspiring model. Ms. Moser had posed her in front of a Greenwich Village garage when some neighborhood children demanded to be in the picture, then began mimicking the model\u2019s poses. The model responded with a crude gesture, captured by Ms. Moser. The Library of Congress purchased the original print in 1998.\"<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nMoser died on August 11, 2014 six days shy of her 94th birthday.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ici.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/arts_et_spectacles/2014/08/13/009-deces-de-la-photographe-lida-moser.shtml|title=Deces de Lida Moser photographe du Quebic desannees 1950|year=2014|author=Sophie Cazenave|website=Radio Canada|access-date=March 25, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\nA documentary of her Canadian travels and photographs was written and directed by Joyce Borenstein and released in 2017 under the title ''Lida Moser Photographer: Odyssey in Black and White''.<ref>{{Citation|title=Lida Moser Photographer: Odyssey in Black and White|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6599250/|access-date=2018-12-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.musee-mccord.qc.ca/en/activities/screening-lida-moser-photographer/|title=Screening of Lida Moser Photographer - McCord Museum|website=Musee McCord|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==Permanent collections==\n\nMoser's work is in the permanent collection of:\n\n*[[Museum of Modern Art]], [[New York City|New York]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moma.org/artists/49613|title=Lida Moser {{!}} MoMA|website=The Museum of Modern Art|language=en|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n*A portrait of Moser, by painter [[Alice Neel]], is in the permanent collection of the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] in New York City.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/484558|title=''Lida Moser'' 1963, Alice Neel| website=www.metmuseum.org|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n*[[Corcoran Gallery]], Washington, DC\n*[[Phillips Collection]], Washington, DC<ref name=\":3\" />\n*[[Biblioth\u00e8que et Archives nationales du Qu\u00e9bec]], [[Quebec City|Quebec]], Canada<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lidamoser.mnbaq.org/|title=Le qu\u00e9bec de Lida Moser|last=|first=|date=|website=Biblioth\u00e8que et Archives nationales du Qu\u00e9bec|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lidamoser.mnbaq.org/biographie/|title=La photographe Lida Moser \u2022 Le qu\u00e9bec de Lida Moser|website=Le qu\u00e9bec de Lida Moser|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theconcordian.com/2016/02/the-1950s-in-quebec-through-the-eyes-of-lida-moser/|title=The 1950s in Quebec through the eyes of Lida Moser|last=Sachet|first=Ambre|date=2016-02-02|website=The Concordian|language=en-CA|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n*[[Library of Congress]], Washington, DC<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/photos/?q=lida+moser|title=Search results for Photo, Print, Drawing, Lida Moser, Available Online|website=Library of Congress, Washington, D.C. 20540 USA|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n*[[Library and Archives Canada]], [[Ottawa]], Canada<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/news/archive/2015/05/something-old-something-new-access-heart-lac-mandate.html|title=Something old, something new: access and the heart of LAC's mandate|last=Canada|first=Service|date=2015-05-12|website=gcnws|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n*[[National Galleries of Scotland]], [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]]<ref name=\"NGS\" /> \n*[[National Portrait Gallery, London]], [[United Kingdom]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp08538/lida-moser |title=Search the Collection Lida Moser (1920-2014)|website= National Portrait Gallery London|access-date=March 25, 2019}}</ref> \n*[[National Portrait Gallery (United States)|National Portrait Gallery]], Washington, DC<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://npg.si.edu/object/npg_NPG.2016.134|title=Judy Collins|website=npg.si.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n*[[New-York Historical Society|New York Historical Society]], New York <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dlib.nyu.edu/findingaids/html/nyhs/moser/|title=Guide to the Lida Moser Photograph Collection New York Historical Society|website=dlib.nyu.edu|access-date=2018-12-19}}</ref>\n*[[Smithsonian Institution]], Washington, DC <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://collections.si.edu/search/results.htm?q=lida%20moser|title=Collections Search Center, Smithsonian Institution|website=collections.si.edu|access-date=2018-12-19}}</ref>\n*[[Museum of Fine Arts, Houston|Museum of Fine Arts]], [[Houston]], [[Texas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://emuseum.mfah.org/objects/26917/aaron-siskind|title=Aaron Siskind Photograph by Lida Moser|last=|first=|date=|website=The Museum of Fine Arts Houston|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n*[[Crystal Bridges Museum of American Art]], [[Bentonville, Arkansas|Bentonville]], [[Arkansas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://crystalbridges.org/blog/womens-history-month-lida-moser/|title=Women\u2019s History Month: Lida Moser|date=2016-03-09|website=Crystal Bridges Museum of American Art|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n*[[Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art]], [[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City]], [[Missouri]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://localhost/people/10644/lida-moser;jsessionid=9EA69A7E21C8959021F2E907F2FE3959|title=Lida Moser \u2013 Artists/Makers \u2013 The Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art|website=localhost|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==Significant works==\n\n*1949 \"Queen's Parade, Edinburgh, Scotland\"<ref name=\"gallery work\" />\n*1949 \"John Boyd Orr, Baron Boyd Orr\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/portrait/mw09875/John-Boyd-Orr-Baron-Boyd-Orr|title=John Boyd Orr, Baron Boyd Orr - National Portrait Gallery|website=www.npg.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n*1949 \"Douglas Young\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/portrait/mw09876/Douglas-Young|title=Douglas Young - National Portrait Gallery|website=www.npg.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n*1949 \"Stanley Cursiter\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/artists/lida-moser|title=Lida Moser {{!}} National Galleries of Scotland|website=www.nationalgalleries.org|language=en|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n*1949 \"Dovecot Studios, Edinburgh Tapestry Company\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/10141/dovecot-studios-edinburgh-tapestry-company-ronnie-mcvinnie-john-loufit-fred-marin-richard-gordon|title=Dovecot Studios, Edinburgh Tapestry Company (Ronnie McVinnie, John Loufit, Fred Marin, Richard Gordon, Alec Jack, Ian Inglis, Archie Brennan,...|website=National Galleries of Scotland|language=en|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n*1950 \"Farm Girls, Valley of the Matapedia, Quebec\"<ref name=\"gallery work\" />\n*1950 \"Two students of Quebec City's Ecole Moderne pose with sculptures\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theconcordian.com/2016/02/the-1950s-in-quebec-through-the-eyes-of-lida-moser/|title=The 1950s in Quebec through the eyes of Lida Moser|date=2016-02-02|website=The Concordian|language=en-CA|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n*1961 \"Judy and the Boys\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.loc.gov/pictures/item/98517055/|title=Mimicry (Judy and the boys)|last=Moser|first=Lida|date=1961|website=www.loc.gov|language=en|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n*1965 \"Office Bldg. Lobby, New York\"<ref name=\"gallery work\" />\n*1968 \"Cops, Times Square, New York\"<ref name=\"gallery work\" />\n*1971 \"Construction of the Exxon Building, New York'<ref name=\"NGS\" /><ref name=\"gallery work\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A62979-2005Mar24.html |title=Lida Moser At Her Finest|work=The Washington Post |accessdate=2012-09-21 |first=Michael |last=O'Sullivan |date=March 25, 2005}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n\n*Earthman, Come Home (1966)\n*A Life For the Stars (Cities in Flight, 2) (Avon SF, G1280) (1968)\n*Construction of the Exxon Building, New York (1971)\n*Fun in Photography Amphoto U.S.(1974) {{ISBN|978-0-8174-056-49}}\n*Amphoto Guide to Special Effects Watson-Guptill Pubns(1980) {{ISBN|978-0-8174-352-40}}\n*'Photography Contests: How to Enter, How to Win Amphoto U.S.(1981){{ISBN|978-0-8174-244-59}}\n*Grants in Photography: How to Get Them (1979){{ISBN|978-0-8174-244-59}}\n*Quebec a l'ete 1950 Libre Expression (French Edition) (1982) {{ISBN|978-2-8911-111-02}}\n*Career Photography: How to Be a Success As a Professional Photographer Prentice Hall Trade (1983){{ISBN|978-0-13115-11-30}} <ref>{{cite news |url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FB0A1EF8355A1A7493C5A8178BD95F428785F9&scp=1&sq=A%20Photographer%27s%20Guide%20to%20Cooperative%20Galleries&st=cse# |title=Lida Moser Amazon Bibliography |work=Amazon.com | date=October 17, 1976}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nMoser's 1971 book  \u201c''Construction of Exxon Building, New York City\"'' features a photo of window washers that has been recreated in Lego building blocks at [[Legoland Miniland New York City|Legoland Florida]] theme park.\n\n''Office Building Lobby, New York'', in which Moser\u2019s wild overexposure has reduced organization men to near\u2013stick figures and the lobby to an ill-defined blob, presaging by several years the visual distortions of [[2001: A Space Odyssey]].<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/03/arts/lida-moser-photographer-with-an-urban-eye-dies-at-93.html Lida Moser obituary in ''The New York Times'']\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moser, Lida}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:American photographers]]\n[[Category:American women photographers]]\n[[Category:Photographers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Photographers from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Photographers from Maryland]]\n[[Category:Artists from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Jewish American artists]]\n[[Category:Street photographers]]\n", "text_old": "<br />\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Lida Moser\n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1920|8|17|mf=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[New York City]], New York\n| death_date         = {{Death date and age|2014|8|11|1920|8|17}}\n| death_place        = [[Rockville, MD]]\n| education          = \n| alma_mater         = \n| occupation         = [[Photographer]], [[author]]\n| years_active       = 1947 &mdash; 2014\n| employer           = \n| known_for          = photojournalism, portraiture, fashion, experimental, street photography\n| notable_works      = Judy and the Boys, 1961\n| spouse             = \n| partner            = \n| children           = \n| parents            = \n| awards             = \n| website            = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n'''Lida Moser''' (August 17, 1920 \u2013 August 11, 2014)<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /> was an American-born [[photographer]] and [[author]], with a career that spanned more than six decades, before retiring in her 90s. She was known for her photojournalism and [[street photography]] as a member of both the [[Photo League]] <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.higherpictures.com/artists/Women_of_the_Photo_League/Works.aspx?s=190 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2012-09-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120103043632/http://www.higherpictures.com/artists/Women_of_the_Photo_League/Works.aspx?s=190 |archivedate=2012-01-03 }} | Women of the Photo League</ref> and the New York School. Her portfolio includes black and white commercial, portrait, landscape, experimental, [[Abstraction|abstract,]] and [[documentary photography]], with her work continuing to have an impact.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe Photo League was an early center of American documentary photography in the post war years, with membership including many of the most significant photographers of the 20th century. In a retrospective at the [[Fraser Gallery]] in Washington DC, she was described as a pioneer in the field of photojournalism,<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|url=http://www.thefrasergallery.com/reviews/LidaMoserWCP2005.html |title=Lida Moser: Fifty Years of Photographs|first=Louis |last=Jacobson |date=8 April 2005 |work=Washington City Paper |accessdate=2012-09-21}}</ref>  and ''The [[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' noted that she \"excelled at photojournalism at a time when women were a rarity in the field.\"<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite news|last=Slotnik|first=Daniel E.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/03/arts/lida-moser-photographer-with-an-urban-eye-dies-at-93.html|title=Lida Moser, Photographer With an Urban Eye, Dies at 93|date=2014-09-02|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-04-15|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> She has also been described, much to Moser's annoyance,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/arts/museums-galleries/blog/13081071/why-photographer-lida-moser-couldnt-be-pigeonholed|title=Why Photographer Lida Moser Couldn't Be Pigeonholed|website=Washington City Paper|language=en|access-date=2018-12-19}}</ref> the ''\"grandmother of American photojournalism.\"''<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/arts/article/13028481/photographic-memories|title=Photographic Memories|website=Washington City Paper|language=en|access-date=2018-12-19}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Judy and the Boys 1961.jpg|300px|thumb| \"Judy and the Boys (Mimicry)\" Photograph by Lida Moser, 1961.]]\nMoser was born in 1920 in New York City.<ref name=\":3\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/lida-moser-photographer-of-new-york-and-beyond-dies-at-93/2014/08/30/ea3fb98a-2ec3-11e4-9b98-848790384093_story.html|title=Lida Moser, photographer of New York and beyond, dies at 93|author=Emily Langer|date=August 30, 2014|work=The Washington Post|accessdate=March 25, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Moser|first=Lidia|title=United States Public Records Index|url=https://familysearch.org|publisher=Family Search|accessdate=28 October 2013}}</ref> Her career started in 1947 as an assistant in [[Berenice Abbott|Berenice Abbott's]] studio.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://montrealgazette.com/news/local-news/photojournalist-made-her-mark-in-quebec/|title=Photojournalist made her mark in Quebec|last=Lalonde|first=Michelle|date=2014-04-14|website=The Montreal Gazette|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> She then earned her first assignment from ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' in 1949, traveling across [[Canada]]. Other magazines featuring her work included ''[[Harper's Bazaar]]'', ''[[Look (American magazine)|Look]]'' and ''[[Esquire (magazine)|Esquire]]''. She authored a number of books of her own work and co-authored several photographic technique books. Articles and ongoing columns appeared in the ''New York Times'', ''New York Sunday Times'', ''Amphoto Guide to Special Effects'', ''Fun in Photography'', ''Career Photography'', ''Women See Men'', ''Women of Vision'' and ''This Was the Photo League'', among others.\n\nIn 1949 Moser was assigned by ''[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]]'' magazine to travel to Scotland and photograph leading [[List of Scottish writers|Scottish writers]] and artists. Over 100 of those photographs are now in the permanent collection of [[National Galleries of Scotland|The National Galleries of Scotland]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/search|title=Artworks {{!}} National Galleries of Scotland - Lida Moser Search|last=|first=|date=|website=www.nationalgalleries.org|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> Moser photographed key artists and writers such as [[James Bridie|James Birdie]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/108702/james-bridie|title=James Bridie|website=National Galleries of Scotland|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> [[Stanley Cursiter]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/108703/stanley-cursiter-1887-1976-artist-his-studio|title=Stanley Cursiter, 1887 - 1976. Artist in his Studio|website=National Galleries of Scotland|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> [[William Crosbie (artist)|William Crosbie]],<ref name=\":5\" /> [[Hugh MacDiarmid]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/108631/christopher-murray-grieve-nom-de-plume-hugh-macdiarmid-1892-1978-poet|title=Christopher Murray Grieve (nom de plume 'Hugh MacDiarmid'), 1892 - 1978. Poet|website=National Galleries of Scotland|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> [[Sorley MacLean]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/108636/sorley-maclean-1911-1996-poet|title=Sorley MacLean, 1911 - 1996. Poet|website=National Galleries of Scotland|language=en|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref> and many others.\n\nMoser\u2019s series of \"Camera View\" articles on photography for ''The New York Times'' appeared between 1974 and 1981.<ref name=\"cooperative galleries\">{{cite web |url=http://www.thefrasergallery.com/reviews/LidaMoserWCP2005.html |title=A Photographer's Guide to Cooperative Galleries; Cooperative Galleries|first=Lida |last=Moser |date=17 October 1976 |work=New York Times |accessdate=2012-09-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.artforum.com/news/lida-moser-1920-2014-48110|title=Lida Moser (1920\u20132014)|website=www.artforum.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> Her photography has fetched as much as $4,000 at Christie's and other auctions<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.artnet.com/artists/lida-moser/past-auction-results|title=Past Auction Results for Lida Moser|website= Artnet.com|accessdate=March 25, 2019}}</ref> and continues to be collected and displayed by more than 40 museums worldwide.<ref name=\"NGS\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/search?search=Lida%20Moser|title= Artworks, 115 artworks, Lida Moser|website=National Galleries Scotland|accessdate= March 25, 2019}}</ref> Moser\u2019s relationship to French photographer [[Eug\u00e8ne Atget]] can be seen in her photographs of [[Edinburgh]] as an early influence and that of American photographer [[Walker Evans]].\n\nMoser was a close friend of American artist [[Alice Neel]], and she photographed Neel several times;<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bangordailynews.com/2014/09/02/living/noted-photographer-lida-moser-dies-at-93/|title=Noted photographer Lida Moser dies at 93|website=Bangor Daily News|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref> in return Neel painted multiple portraits of Moser, which now hang is several museums in the U.S.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nAccording to ''The New York Times'', \"Perhaps her most famous photograph, \u201cMimicry ([[:File:Judy and the Boys 1961.jpg|Judy and the Boys]])\u201d (1961), began as a shoot for an aspiring model. Ms. Moser had posed her in front of a Greenwich Village garage when some neighborhood children demanded to be in the picture, then began mimicking the model\u2019s poses. The model responded with a crude gesture, captured by Ms. Moser. The Library of Congress purchased the original print in 1998.\"<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nMoser died on August 11, 2014 six days shy of her 94th birthday.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ici.radio-canada.ca/nouvelles/arts_et_spectacles/2014/08/13/009-deces-de-la-photographe-lida-moser.shtml|title=Deces de Lida Moser photographe du Quebic desannees 1950|year=2014|author=Sophie Cazenave|website=Radio Canada|access-date=March 25, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\nA documentary of her Canadian travels and photographs was written and directed by Joyce Borenstein and released in 2017 under the title ''Lida Moser Photographer: Odyssey in Black and White''.<ref>{{Citation|title=Lida Moser Photographer: Odyssey in Black and White|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt6599250/|access-date=2018-12-19}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.musee-mccord.qc.ca/en/activities/screening-lida-moser-photographer/|title=Screening of Lida Moser Photographer - McCord Museum|website=Musee McCord|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==Permanent collections==\n\nMoser's work is in the permanent collection of:\n\n*[[Museum of Modern Art]], [[New York City|New York]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.moma.org/artists/49613|title=Lida Moser {{!}} MoMA|website=The Museum of Modern Art|language=en|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n*A portrait of Moser, by painter [[Alice Neel]], is in the permanent collection of the [[Metropolitan Museum of Art]] in New York City.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/484558|title=''Lida Moser'' 1963, Alice Neel| website=www.metmuseum.org|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n*[[Corcoran Gallery]], Washington, DC\n*[[Phillips Collection]], Washington, DC<ref name=\":3\" />\n*[[Biblioth\u00e8que et Archives nationales du Qu\u00e9bec]], [[Quebec City|Quebec]], Canada<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lidamoser.mnbaq.org/|title=Le qu\u00e9bec de Lida Moser|last=|first=|date=|website=Biblioth\u00e8que et Archives nationales du Qu\u00e9bec|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://lidamoser.mnbaq.org/biographie/|title=La photographe Lida Moser \u2022 Le qu\u00e9bec de Lida Moser|website=Le qu\u00e9bec de Lida Moser|language=fr|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theconcordian.com/2016/02/the-1950s-in-quebec-through-the-eyes-of-lida-moser/|title=The 1950s in Quebec through the eyes of Lida Moser|last=Sachet|first=Ambre|date=2016-02-02|website=The Concordian|language=en-CA|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n*[[Library of Congress]], Washington, DC<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.loc.gov/photos/?q=lida+moser|title=Search results for Photo, Print, Drawing, Lida Moser, Available Online|website=Library of Congress, Washington, D.C. 20540 USA|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" />\n*[[Library and Archives Canada]], [[Ottawa]], Canada<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/news/archive/2015/05/something-old-something-new-access-heart-lac-mandate.html|title=Something old, something new: access and the heart of LAC's mandate|last=Canada|first=Service|date=2015-05-12|website=gcnws|access-date=2020-04-16}}</ref>\n*[[National Galleries of Scotland]], [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]]<ref name=\"NGS\" /> \n*[[National Portrait Gallery, London]], [[United Kingdom]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/person/mp08538/lida-moser |title=Search the Collection Lida Moser (1920-2014)|website= National Portrait Gallery London|access-date=March 25, 2019}}</ref> \n*[[National Portrait Gallery (United States)|National Portrait Gallery]], Washington, DC<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://npg.si.edu/object/npg_NPG.2016.134|title=Judy Collins|website=npg.si.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n*[[New-York Historical Society|New York Historical Society]], New York <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dlib.nyu.edu/findingaids/html/nyhs/moser/|title=Guide to the Lida Moser Photograph Collection New York Historical Society|website=dlib.nyu.edu|access-date=2018-12-19}}</ref>\n*[[Smithsonian Institution]], Washington, DC <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://collections.si.edu/search/results.htm?q=lida%20moser|title=Collections Search Center, Smithsonian Institution|website=collections.si.edu|access-date=2018-12-19}}</ref>\n*[[Museum of Fine Arts, Houston|Museum of Fine Arts]], [[Houston]], [[Texas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://emuseum.mfah.org/objects/26917/aaron-siskind|title=Aaron Siskind Photograph by Lida Moser|last=|first=|date=|website=The Museum of Fine Arts Houston|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n*[[Crystal Bridges Museum of American Art]], [[Bentonville, Arkansas|Bentonville]], [[Arkansas]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://crystalbridges.org/blog/womens-history-month-lida-moser/|title=Women\u2019s History Month: Lida Moser|date=2016-03-09|website=Crystal Bridges Museum of American Art|language=en-CA|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n*[[Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art]], [[Kansas City, Missouri|Kansas City]], [[Missouri]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://localhost/people/10644/lida-moser;jsessionid=9EA69A7E21C8959021F2E907F2FE3959|title=Lida Moser \u2013 Artists/Makers \u2013 The Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art|website=localhost|language=en|access-date=2020-04-15}}</ref>\n\n==Significant works==\n\n*1949 \"Queen's Parade, Edinburgh, Scotland\"<ref name=\"gallery work\" />\n*1949 \"John Boyd Orr, Baron Boyd Orr\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/portrait/mw09875/John-Boyd-Orr-Baron-Boyd-Orr|title=John Boyd Orr, Baron Boyd Orr - National Portrait Gallery|website=www.npg.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n*1949 \"Douglas Young\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.npg.org.uk/collections/search/portrait/mw09876/Douglas-Young|title=Douglas Young - National Portrait Gallery|website=www.npg.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n*1949 \"Stanley Cursiter\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/artists/lida-moser|title=Lida Moser {{!}} National Galleries of Scotland|website=www.nationalgalleries.org|language=en|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n*1949 \"Dovecot Studios, Edinburgh Tapestry Company\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nationalgalleries.org/art-and-artists/10141/dovecot-studios-edinburgh-tapestry-company-ronnie-mcvinnie-john-loufit-fred-marin-richard-gordon|title=Dovecot Studios, Edinburgh Tapestry Company (Ronnie McVinnie, John Loufit, Fred Marin, Richard Gordon, Alec Jack, Ian Inglis, Archie Brennan,...|website=National Galleries of Scotland|language=en|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n*1950 \"Farm Girls, Valley of the Matapedia, Quebec\"<ref name=\"gallery work\" />\n*1950 \"Two students of Quebec City's Ecole Moderne pose with sculptures\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://theconcordian.com/2016/02/the-1950s-in-quebec-through-the-eyes-of-lida-moser/|title=The 1950s in Quebec through the eyes of Lida Moser|date=2016-02-02|website=The Concordian|language=en-CA|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n*1961 \"Judy and the Boys\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.loc.gov/pictures/item/98517055/|title=Mimicry (Judy and the boys)|last=Moser|first=Lida|date=1961|website=www.loc.gov|language=en|access-date=2019-02-13}}</ref>\n*1965 \"Office Bldg. Lobby, New York\"<ref name=\"gallery work\" />\n*1968 \"Cops, Times Square, New York\"<ref name=\"gallery work\" />\n*1971 \"Construction of the Exxon Building, New York'<ref name=\"NGS\" /><ref name=\"gallery work\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/articles/A62979-2005Mar24.html |title=Lida Moser At Her Finest|work=The Washington Post |accessdate=2012-09-21 |first=Michael |last=O'Sullivan |date=March 25, 2005}}</ref>\n\n==Books==\n\n*Earthman, Come Home (1966)\n*A Life For the Stars (Cities in Flight, 2) (Avon SF, G1280) (1968)\n*Construction of the Exxon Building, New York (1971)\n*Fun in Photography Amphoto U.S.(1974) {{ISBN|978-0-8174-056-49}}\n*Amphoto Guide to Special Effects Watson-Guptill Pubns(1980) {{ISBN|978-0-8174-352-40}}\n*'Photography Contests: How to Enter, How to Win Amphoto U.S.(1981){{ISBN|978-0-8174-244-59}}\n*Grants in Photography: How to Get Them (1979){{ISBN|978-0-8174-244-59}}\n*Quebec a l'ete 1950 Libre Expression (French Edition) (1982) {{ISBN|978-2-8911-111-02}}\n*Career Photography: How to Be a Success As a Professional Photographer Prentice Hall Trade (1983){{ISBN|978-0-13115-11-30}} <ref>{{cite news |url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FB0A1EF8355A1A7493C5A8178BD95F428785F9&scp=1&sq=A%20Photographer%27s%20Guide%20to%20Cooperative%20Galleries&st=cse# |title=Lida Moser Amazon Bibliography |work=Amazon.com | date=October 17, 1976}}</ref>\n\n==In popular culture==\nMoser's 1971 book  \u201c''Construction of Exxon Building, New York City\"'' features a photo of window washers that has been recreated in Lego building blocks at [[Legoland Miniland New York City|Legoland Florida]] theme park.\n\n''Office Building Lobby, New York'', in which Moser\u2019s wild overexposure has reduced organization men to near\u2013stick figures and the lobby to an ill-defined blob, presaging by several years the visual distortions of [[2001: A Space Odyssey]].<ref name=\":4\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n*[https://www.nytimes.com/2014/09/03/arts/lida-moser-photographer-with-an-urban-eye-dies-at-93.html Lida Moser obituary in ''The New York Times'']\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Moser, Lida}}\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:American photographers]]\n[[Category:American women photographers]]\n[[Category:Photographers from New York City]]\n[[Category:Photographers from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Photographers from Maryland]]\n[[Category:Artists from Washington, D.C.]]\n[[Category:Jewish American artists]]\n[[Category:Street photographers]]\n", "name_user": "BoriquaZurdo", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lida_Moser"}
{"title_page": "FMovies", "text_new": "{{short description|Piracy website}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name = FMovies\n| logo = FMovies Logo.png\n| logo_size = \n| logo_alt = \n| logo_caption = \n| screenshot = FMovies Homepage Screenshot.jpg\n| collapsible = \n| collapsetext = \n| background = \n| screenshot_size = \n| screenshot_alt = \n| caption = FMovies Homepage as of June 2019\n| url = {{URL|https://www.fmovies.wtf/}}\n| commercial = No\n| type = [[Streaming media|Online Video Streaming]]\n| registration = Yes\n| language = English\n| area_served = Worldwide (blocked in [[Australia]], [[Sweden]] and [[India]])\n| num_users = \n| content_license = \n| programming_language = [[HTML]], [[JavaScript]] and [[PHP]]\n| owner = unknown\n| author = unknown\n| editor = \n| launch_date = {{Start date and age|2016}}\n| revenue = \n| alexa = {{decrease}} 1,289 ({{as of|2020|04|15|alt=April 2020}})<ref name=\"alexa\">{{cite web |url= https://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/fmovies.to |title=FMovies.to Site Info |work=[[Alexa Internet|Alexa]] |date=August 2019 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n| ip = \n| issn = \n| eissn = \n| oclc = \n| current_status = Online\n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''FMovies''' is a series of websites that host links and [[HTML element|embedded videos]], allowing users to stream or download movies for free.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/court-orders-swedish-isp-telia-to-block-the-pirate-bay-181016/|title=Court Orders Swedish ISP Telia to Block The Pirate Bay & FMovies|date=2018-10-16|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/fmovies-loses-control-of-swedish-domain-moves-to-iceland-180907/|title=FMovies Loses Control of Swedish Domain, Moves to Iceland|date=2018-09-07|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/major-pirate-movie-streaming-site-fmovies-sued-in-us-court-161026/|title=Major 'Pirate' Movie Streaming Site Fmovies Sued in US Court|date=2016-10-26|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/us-court-orders-pirate-streaming-site-fmovies-to-pay-210000-170609/|title=US Court Orders Pirate Streaming Site FMovies to Pay $210,000|date=2017-06-09|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe site was created sometime in 2016 according to ''[[TorrentFreak]],''<ref name=\":2\" /> and blocked from [[Google]] searches in December 2016.\n\nIn October 2017, FMovies lost a lawsuit brought by Filipino media and entertainment group [[ABS-CBN]], and was ordered to pay $210,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/abs-cbn-wants-210000-piracy-damages-from-fmovies-170401/|title=ABS-CBN Wants $210,000 Piracy Damages From FMovies|date=2017-04-01|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fossbytes.com/fmovies-shutdown-possible-court-domain-lawsuit/|title=Will FMovies Soon Lose Its Domain Name? Court Orders The Site To Pay $210,000|last=Verma|first=Adarsh|date=2017-06-10|website=Fossbytes|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mobipicker.com/fmovies-copyright-lawsuit/|title=FMovies.to and FMovies.se to Shut Down Soon? US Court Orders To Pay $210,000 In Copyright Infringement Lawsuit|last=Sharma|first=Shubham|date=2017-06-11|website=MobiPicker|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, the site was identified as a ''Notorious Market'' by the U.S. government, along with [[The Pirate Bay]] and other piracy sites.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/us-govt-brands-torrent-streaming-cyberlocker-sites-as-notorious-markets-180115/|title=US Govt Brands Torrent, Streaming & Cyberlocker Sites As Notorious Markets|date=2018-01-15|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, [[Telia Company]], a Swedish ISP, was ordered to block FMovies.<ref name=\":0\" /> They appealed the order.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/swedish-isp-telia-appeals-pirate-bay-blocking-order-181026/|title=Swedish ISP Telia Appeals Pirate Bay Blocking Order|date=2018-10-26|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>  That same month, the [[Motion Picture Association of America]] reported FMovies along with other piracy sites to the U.S. government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/mpaa-reports-notorious-piracy-threats-to-the-us-government-181003/|title=MPAA Reports 'Notorious' Pirate Sites to The US Government|date=2018-10-03|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\nFMovies was blocked in Australia in December 2018, after a request in August.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/australian-court-orders-blocking-of-subtitle-piracy-sites/|title=Australian court orders blocking of subtitle piracy sites|last=Barbaschow|first=Asha|website=ZDNet|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/australian-court-orders-isps-to-block-181-pirate-domains-including-subtitle-sites-181220/|title=Australian Court Orders ISPs to Block 181 'Pirate' Domains, Including Subtitle Sites|date=2018-12-20|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/movie-tv-show-companies-want-subtitle-sites-blocked-down-under-180802/|title=Movie & TV Show Companies Want Subtitle Sites Blocked Down Under|date=2018-08-02|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, Sweden asked advertisers to blacklist some piracy and streaming sites, which included FMovies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/sweden-asks-advertisers-to-blacklist-streaming-and-torrent-sites-190223/|title=Sweden Asks Advertisers to Blacklist Streaming and Torrent Sites|date=2019-02-23|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techdoctoruk.com/tech-news/sweden-asks-advertisers-to-blacklist-streaming-and-torrent-sites/|title=Sweden Asks Advertisers to Blacklist Streaming and Torrent Sites \u2013 TechDoctorUK|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://letscrackon.org/sweden-asks-advertisers-to-blacklist-streaming-and-torrent-sites/|title=Sweden Asks Advertisers to Blacklist Streaming and Torrent Sites|last=Tech|first=Free|date=2019-02-23|website=Let's Crack On|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.docsquiffy.com/2019/02/23/sweden-asks-advertisers-to-blacklist-streaming-and-torrent-sites/|title=Sweden Asks Advertisers to Blacklist Streaming and Torrent Sites|last=Squiffy|first=Doc|date=2019-02-23|website=DocSquiffy.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-05-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190525142255/https://www.docsquiffy.com/2019/02/23/sweden-asks-advertisers-to-blacklist-streaming-and-torrent-sites/|archive-date=2019-05-25|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Torrentfreak/~3/lG8texke7kk/|title=Sweden Asks Advertisers to Blacklist Streaming and Torrent Sites|date=2019-02-23|website=Husham.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\nBy April 2019, ISPs in India were ordered to block FMovies,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/pirate-bay-rarbg-1337x-torrentz2-to-be-permanently-blocked-in-india-190412/|title=Pirate Bay, RARBG, 1337x & Torrentz2 to be Permanently Blocked in India|date=2019-04-12|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.technadu.com/isps-india-ordered-block-pirate-bay-torrentz2-yts-1337x/64592/|title=ISPs in India Ordered to Block Pirate Bay, Torrentz2, YTS, and 1337x|last=Toulas|first=Bill|date=2019-04-12|website=TechNadu|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techworm.net/2019/04/isp-india-permanently-block-the-pirate-bay-rarbg-1337x-torrentz2.html|title=ISPs in India ordered to permanently block The Pirate Bay, RARBG, 1337x, Torrentz2 and others \u00bb TechWorm|last=techbug9|date=2019-04-13|website=TechWorm|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref> and the U.S. Government identified the site as one of the top piracy sites.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/us-govt-identifies-top-pirate-sites-and-other-notorious-markets-190426/|title=US Govt Identifies Top Pirate Sites and Other 'Notorious Markets'|date=2019-04-26|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.technadu.com/ustr-2018-online-piracy-marketplace-list/65995/|title=USTR Released Their 2018 Online Piracy and Marketplace 'Naughty' List|last=Toulas|first=Bill|date=2019-04-27|website=TechNadu|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\nAs of November 2019, there are 2 to 4 different FMovies websites running, but their locations are unknown.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Putlocker]], similar online movie streaming network\n* [[YIFY]] Torrents (or YTS Torrents), online movie file downloading network\n* [[Popcorn Time]], a [[freeware]] program allowing users to watch movies through torrenting on several platforms\n* [[123Movies|123movies]], similar online movie streaming network\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[https://www.techwiki.in/fmovies-proxy-sites/ Fmovies Proxy is still available on Internet]\n\n== External links ==\n[[Category:BitTorrent websites]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Piracy website}}\n{{Infobox website\n| name = FMovies\n| logo = FMovies Logo.png\n| logo_size = \n| logo_alt = \n| logo_caption = \n| screenshot = FMovies Homepage Screenshot.jpg\n| collapsible = \n| collapsetext = \n| background = \n| screenshot_size = \n| screenshot_alt = \n| caption = FMovies Homepage as of June 2019\n| url = {{URL|https://www.fmovies.wtf/}}\n| commercial = No\n| type = [[Streaming media|Online Video Streaming]]\n| registration = Yes\n| language = English\n| area_served = Worldwide (blocked in [[Australia]], [[Sweden]] and [[India]])\n| num_users = \n| content_license = \n| programming_language = [[HTML]], [[JavaScript]] and [[PHP]]\n| owner = unknown\n| author = unknown\n| editor = \n| launch_date = {{Start date and age|2016}}\n| revenue = \n| alexa = {{decrease}} 1,289 ({{as of|2020|04|15|alt=April 2020}})<ref name=\"alexa\">{{cite web |url= https://www.alexa.com/siteinfo/fmovies.to |title=FMovies.to Site Info |work=[[Alexa Internet|Alexa]] |date=August 2019 |accessdate=15 April 2020}}</ref>\n| ip = \n| issn = \n| eissn = \n| oclc = \n| current_status = Online\n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''FMovies''' is a series of websites that host links and [[HTML element|embedded videos]], allowing users to stream or download movies for free.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/court-orders-swedish-isp-telia-to-block-the-pirate-bay-181016/|title=Court Orders Swedish ISP Telia to Block The Pirate Bay & FMovies|date=2018-10-16|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/fmovies-loses-control-of-swedish-domain-moves-to-iceland-180907/|title=FMovies Loses Control of Swedish Domain, Moves to Iceland|date=2018-09-07|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/major-pirate-movie-streaming-site-fmovies-sued-in-us-court-161026/|title=Major 'Pirate' Movie Streaming Site Fmovies Sued in US Court|date=2016-10-26|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/us-court-orders-pirate-streaming-site-fmovies-to-pay-210000-170609/|title=US Court Orders Pirate Streaming Site FMovies to Pay $210,000|date=2017-06-09|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-03-07}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nThe site was created sometime in 2016 according to ''[[TorrentFreak]],''<ref name=\":2\" /> and blocked from [[Google]] searches in December 2016.\n\nIn October 2017, FMovies lost a lawsuit brought by Filipino media and entertainment group [[ABS-CBN]], and was ordered to pay $210,000.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/abs-cbn-wants-210000-piracy-damages-from-fmovies-170401/|title=ABS-CBN Wants $210,000 Piracy Damages From FMovies|date=2017-04-01|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fossbytes.com/fmovies-shutdown-possible-court-domain-lawsuit/|title=Will FMovies Soon Lose Its Domain Name? Court Orders The Site To Pay $210,000|last=Verma|first=Adarsh|date=2017-06-10|website=Fossbytes|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mobipicker.com/fmovies-copyright-lawsuit/|title=FMovies.to and FMovies.se to Shut Down Soon? US Court Orders To Pay $210,000 In Copyright Infringement Lawsuit|last=Sharma|first=Shubham|date=2017-06-11|website=MobiPicker|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, the site was identified as a ''Notorious Market'' by the U.S. government, along with [[The Pirate Bay]] and other piracy sites.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/us-govt-brands-torrent-streaming-cyberlocker-sites-as-notorious-markets-180115/|title=US Govt Brands Torrent, Streaming & Cyberlocker Sites As Notorious Markets|date=2018-01-15|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, [[Telia Company]], a Swedish ISP, was ordered to block FMovies.<ref name=\":0\" /> They appealed the order.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/swedish-isp-telia-appeals-pirate-bay-blocking-order-181026/|title=Swedish ISP Telia Appeals Pirate Bay Blocking Order|date=2018-10-26|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>  That same month, the [[Motion Picture Association of America]] reported FMovies along with other piracy sites to the U.S. government.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/mpaa-reports-notorious-piracy-threats-to-the-us-government-181003/|title=MPAA Reports 'Notorious' Pirate Sites to The US Government|date=2018-10-03|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\nFMovies was blocked in Australia in December 2018, after a request in August.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.zdnet.com/article/australian-court-orders-blocking-of-subtitle-piracy-sites/|title=Australian court orders blocking of subtitle piracy sites|last=Barbaschow|first=Asha|website=ZDNet|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/australian-court-orders-isps-to-block-181-pirate-domains-including-subtitle-sites-181220/|title=Australian Court Orders ISPs to Block 181 'Pirate' Domains, Including Subtitle Sites|date=2018-12-20|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/movie-tv-show-companies-want-subtitle-sites-blocked-down-under-180802/|title=Movie & TV Show Companies Want Subtitle Sites Blocked Down Under|date=2018-08-02|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, Sweden asked advertisers to blacklist some piracy and streaming sites, which included FMovies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/sweden-asks-advertisers-to-blacklist-streaming-and-torrent-sites-190223/|title=Sweden Asks Advertisers to Blacklist Streaming and Torrent Sites|date=2019-02-23|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techdoctoruk.com/tech-news/sweden-asks-advertisers-to-blacklist-streaming-and-torrent-sites/|title=Sweden Asks Advertisers to Blacklist Streaming and Torrent Sites \u2013 TechDoctorUK|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://letscrackon.org/sweden-asks-advertisers-to-blacklist-streaming-and-torrent-sites/|title=Sweden Asks Advertisers to Blacklist Streaming and Torrent Sites|last=Tech|first=Free|date=2019-02-23|website=Let's Crack On|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.docsquiffy.com/2019/02/23/sweden-asks-advertisers-to-blacklist-streaming-and-torrent-sites/|title=Sweden Asks Advertisers to Blacklist Streaming and Torrent Sites|last=Squiffy|first=Doc|date=2019-02-23|website=DocSquiffy.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-05-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190525142255/https://www.docsquiffy.com/2019/02/23/sweden-asks-advertisers-to-blacklist-streaming-and-torrent-sites/|archive-date=2019-05-25|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/Torrentfreak/~3/lG8texke7kk/|title=Sweden Asks Advertisers to Blacklist Streaming and Torrent Sites|date=2019-02-23|website=Husham.com|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\nBy April 2019, ISPs in India were ordered to block FMovies,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/pirate-bay-rarbg-1337x-torrentz2-to-be-permanently-blocked-in-india-190412/|title=Pirate Bay, RARBG, 1337x & Torrentz2 to be Permanently Blocked in India|date=2019-04-12|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.technadu.com/isps-india-ordered-block-pirate-bay-torrentz2-yts-1337x/64592/|title=ISPs in India Ordered to Block Pirate Bay, Torrentz2, YTS, and 1337x|last=Toulas|first=Bill|date=2019-04-12|website=TechNadu|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.techworm.net/2019/04/isp-india-permanently-block-the-pirate-bay-rarbg-1337x-torrentz2.html|title=ISPs in India ordered to permanently block The Pirate Bay, RARBG, 1337x, Torrentz2 and others \u00bb TechWorm|last=techbug9|date=2019-04-13|website=TechWorm|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref> and the U.S. Government identified the site as one of the top piracy sites.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://torrentfreak.com/us-govt-identifies-top-pirate-sites-and-other-notorious-markets-190426/|title=US Govt Identifies Top Pirate Sites and Other 'Notorious Markets'|date=2019-04-26|website=TorrentFreak|language=en|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.technadu.com/ustr-2018-online-piracy-marketplace-list/65995/|title=USTR Released Their 2018 Online Piracy and Marketplace 'Naughty' List|last=Toulas|first=Bill|date=2019-04-27|website=TechNadu|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-25}}</ref>\n\nAs of November 2019, there are 2 to 4 different FMovies websites running, but their locations are unknown.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Putlocker]], similar online movie streaming network\n* [[YIFY]] Torrents (or YTS Torrents), online movie file downloading network\n* [[Popcorn Time]], a [[freeware]] program allowing users to watch movies through torrenting on several platforms\n* [[123Movies|123movies]], similar online movie streaming network\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n[[Category:BitTorrent websites]]\n", "name_user": "Piyushdr", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/FMovies"}
